# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: claire-house-children-s-hospice
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] Bebington was an ancient parish, which included the two villages of **Lower Bebington** around the parish church of St Andrew's and **Higher Bebington** to the west, as well as several other surrounding hamlets.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] Following the 2021 census, the Office for National Statistics defined a Bebington built up area which had a population of 57,600.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] The Bebington electoral ward covers a much smaller area around the original village centres of Higher Bebington and Lower Bebington.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] Some definitions of Bebington include adjoining areas such as Port Sunlight (an early planned factory town), New Ferry, Spital and Storeton.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] The former Municipal Borough of Bebington, a local authority between 1937 and 1974, also included within its boundaries Bromborough, Eastham, Raby, Thornton Hough and Brimstage, which now fall within the electoral wards of Bromborough, Eastham and Clatterbridge.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] According to a 2015 study commissioned by Royal Mail from the Centre for Economic and Business Research, Bebington's postcode area, CH63, is the most desirable in England in which to live and work.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] The study found that the area had "the ideal balance" of housing close to places of work, good schools and high employment.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] The name Bebington is derived from the Anglo-Saxon meaning the "Village of Bebba", probably a Saxon chief or landowner.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] Mention of the battle is made in dozens of sources, in Old English, Latin, Irish, Welsh, Anglo-Norman and Middle English, and there are many later accounts or responses to the battle.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] A contemporary record of the battle is found in the Old English poem Battle of Brunanburh, preserved in the Anglo-Saxon Chronicle.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] Andrew, on a site occupied since Saxon times, dates from the 14th and 16th centuries.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] In 1801, Bebington was a small country hamlet with a population of only 273, situated on the main road connecting Chester and Birkenhead, and then via ferry to Liverpool.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] Up to 30 horse-drawn coaches would pass by each day.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] By 1840, the Birkenhead to Chester railway was running and in 1844 the New Chester Road opened and Bebington lost its coaching traffic.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] In 1838, the footprints of an archosaur later called the *Chirotherium storetonese* were found in a sandstone bed at Storeton Quarry.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] Examples can be seen at the Liverpool Museum and at Christ Church within the parish of Higher Bebington.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] Also a small example can be seen at Higher Bebington Junior School, in their reception area.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] Stone quarried at Bebington was used for the construction of Birkenhead Town Hall, some of the villas around Birkenhead and Rock Parks and most famously of all the Empire State Building in New York City.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] The stone is considered to be a high quality sandstone which is creamy in appearance.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] The quarries were eventually filled in with debris removed during the construction of the two Mersey Tunnels.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] Mayer Hall, in Lower Bebington village, was formerly an art gallery built by Bebington philanthropist Joseph Mayer, a noted antiquarian, whose collection of Anglo-Saxon antiquaries helped in the development of British archaeology.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] It is still a community resource and boasts many of its original features.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] Bebington is on the eastern side of the Wirral Peninsula, approximately 10 km (6.2 mi) south-south-east of the Irish Sea at New Brighton, about 7.5 km (4.7 mi) east-north-east of the Dee Estuary at Gayton and less than 2 km (1.2 mi) west-north-west of the River Mersey at New Ferry.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] The area is situated at an elevation of between 20–60 m (66–197 ft) above sea level.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] There is one main tier of local government covering Bebington, at metropolitan borough level: Wirral Council.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] The council is a member of the Liverpool City Region Combined Authority, which is led by the directly-elected Mayor of the Liverpool City Region.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] Bebington was an ancient parish in the Wirral Hundred of Cheshire.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] The parish was subdivided into five townships, called Higher Bebington, Lower Bebington, Poulton cum Spital, Storeton, and Tranmere.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] The original parish church, St Andrew's, is at Lower Bebington.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] From the 17th century onwards, parishes were gradually given various civil functions under the poor laws, in addition to their original ecclesiastical functions.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] In some cases, including Bebington, the civil functions were exercised by each township separately rather than the parish as a whole.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] In 1866, the legal definition of 'parish' was changed to be the areas used for administering the poor laws, and so each township became a separate civil parish.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] Local government districts, each governed by an elected local board, were established in 1859 for Higher Bebington, in 1860 for Tranmere, and in 1863 for Lower Bebington.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] The Tranmere district was abolished in 1877 and its area incorporated into the borough of Birkenhead.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] Port Sunlight was developed from 1888 on land within the Lower Bebington district.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] Local government districts were reconstituted as urban districts under the Local Government Act 1894.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] Lower Bebington Urban District Council bought Pennant House to serve as its headquarters in 1901, using the adjoining Mayer Hall as its council chamber.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] The three urban districts of Lower Bebington, Higher Bebington and neighbouring Bromborough to the south were merged into a single Bebington and Bromborough Urban District in 1922.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] The urban district was renamed Bebington in 1933, when its territory was also significantly enlarged to take in the neighbouring parishes of Storeton, Poulton cum Spital, Brimstage, Thornton Hough, Raby, and Eastham.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] The urban district council was granted a coat of arms in 1934.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] Bebington Urban District was raised to the status of a municipal borough in 1937.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] A new Town Hall was built opposite Pennant House in 1955 as one of the first phases of a wider civic centre.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] The borough council continued to meet at Mayer Hall until a new council chamber was completed in 1971 as one of the later phases of the civic centre complex, forming part of the same building as Bebington Central Library.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] The borough of Bebington was abolished in 1974 under the Local Government Act 1972.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] The area became part of the Metropolitan Borough of Wirral in the new county of Merseyside.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] The Oval Sports Centre was used in the film, *Chariots of Fire*, to portray the 1924 Colombes Olympic Stadium in Paris.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/bebington] In March 1942 after a successful ‘Warship Week’ National Savings campaign HMS Sabre (H18) was adopted by the civil community of Bebington, Cheshire, the same month she was detached for escort of the Russian Convoy PQ 13 during its initial stage of passage to Iceland in the Northwest Approaches.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The county has an area of 905 square miles (2,344 km2) and had a population of 1,139,884 in 2024.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The areas around the River Mersey in the north of the county are the most densely populated, with Warrington, Runcorn, Widnes, and Ellesmere Port located on the river.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The city of Chester lies in the west of the county, Crewe in the south, and Macclesfield in the east.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] For local government purposes Cheshire comprises four unitary authority areas: Cheshire East, Cheshire West and Chester, Halton, and Warrington.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Halton Borough Council is a member of the Liverpool City Region Combined Authority, and the councils of the other three areas collaborate through the Cheshire and Warrington Combined Authority.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The county historically included all of the Wirral Peninsula and parts of southern Greater Manchester and northern Derbyshire, but excluded Widnes and Warrington.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The landscape of the county is dominated by the Cheshire Plain, an area of relatively flat land divided by the Mid-Cheshire Ridge.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] To the west, Cheshire contains the south of the Wirral Peninsula, and to the east the landscape rises to the Pennines, where the county contains part of the Peak District.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The River Mersey runs through the north of Cheshire before broadening into its wide estuary; the River Dee forms part of the county's border with Wales, then fully enters England and flows through Chester before re-entering Wales upstream of its estuary.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Red Triassic sandstone forms the bedrock of much of the county, and was used in the construction of many of its buildings.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Cheshire's name was originally derived from an early name for Chester, and was first recorded as *Legeceasterscir* in the *Anglo-Saxon Chronicle*, meaning "the shire of the city of legions".
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Although the name first appears in 980, it is thought that the county was created by Edward the Elder around 920.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] In the Domesday Book, Cheshire was recorded as having the name *Cestrescir* (Chestershire), derived from the name for Chester at the time.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Through the next few centuries a series of changes that occurred in the English language, which have included simplifications and elision, has resulted in the name Cheshire.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Because of the historically close links with the land bordering Cheshire to the west, which became modern Wales, there is a history of interaction between Cheshire and North Wales.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The Domesday Book records Cheshire as having two complete Hundreds (Atiscross and Exestan) that later became the principal part of Flintshire.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Additionally, another large portion of the Duddestan Hundred later became known as English Maelor (Maelor Saesneg) when it was transferred to North Wales.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] For this and other reasons, the Welsh language name for Cheshire, *Swydd Gaerlleon*, is sometimes used.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] After the Norman Conquest of 1066 by William I, dissent and resistance continued for many years after the invasion.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] In 1069 local resistance in Cheshire was finally put down using draconian measures as part of the Harrying of the North.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The ferocity of the campaign against the English populace was enough to end all future resistance.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Examples were made of major landowners such as Earl Edwin of Mercia, their properties confiscated and redistributed amongst Norman barons.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The earldom was sufficiently independent from the kingdom of England that the 13th-century Magna Carta did not apply to the shire of Chester, so the earl wrote up his own Chester Charter at the petition of his barons.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] William I made Cheshire a county palatine and gave Gerbod the Fleming the new title of Earl of Chester.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] When Gerbod returned to Normandy in about 1070, the king used his absence to declare the earldom forfeit and gave the title to Hugh d'Avranches (nicknamed Hugh Lupus, or "wolf").
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Because of Cheshire's strategic location on the Welsh Marches, the Earl had complete autonomous powers to rule on behalf of the king in the county palatine.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Cheshire in the Domesday Book (1086) is recorded as a much larger county than it is today.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] It included two hundreds, Atiscross and Exestan, that later became part of North Wales.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] At the time of the Domesday Book, it also included as part of Duddestan Hundred the area of land later known as English Maelor (which used to be a detached part of Flintshire) in Wales.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The area between the Mersey and Ribble (referred to in the Domesday Book as "Inter Ripam et Mersam") formed part of the returns for Cheshire.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Although this has been interpreted to mean that at that time south Lancashire was part of Cheshire, more exhaustive research indicates that the boundary between Cheshire and what was to become Lancashire remained the River Mersey.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] With minor variations in spelling across sources, the complete list of hundreds of Cheshire at this time are: Atiscross, Bochelau, Chester, Dudestan, Exestan, Hamestan, Middlewich, Riseton, Roelau, Tunendune, Warmundestrou and Wilaveston.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] There were 8 feudal baronies in Chester, the barons of Kinderton, Halton, Malbank, Mold, Shipbrook, Dunham-Massey, and the honour of Chester itself.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Feudal baronies or baronies by tenure were granted by the Earl as forms of feudal land tenure within the palatinate in a similar way to which the king granted English feudal baronies within England proper.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] One of Hugh d'Avranche's barons has been identified as Robert Nicholls, Baron of Halton and Montebourg.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] In 1182, the land north of the Mersey became administered as part of the new county of Lancashire, resolving any uncertainty about the county in which the land "Inter Ripam et Mersam" was.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Over the years, the ten hundreds consolidated and changed names to leave just seven—Broxton, Bucklow, Eddisbury, Macclesfield, Nantwich, Northwich and Wirral.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] In 1397 the county had lands in the march of Wales added to its territory, and was promoted to the rank of principality.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] This was because of the support the men of the county had given to King Richard II, in particular by his standing armed force of about 500 men called the "Cheshire Guard".
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] As a result, the King's title was changed to "King of England and France, Lord of Ireland, and Prince of Chester".
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] No other English county has been honoured in this way, although it lost the distinction on Richard's fall in 1399.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The Redcliffe-Maud Report of 1969 suggested that Cheshire be abolished as an administrative county, with its parts subdivided between Merseyside, Stoke-on-Trent and [what was then called] South-East Lancashire & North East Cheshire (SELNEC).
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] A series of compromises between the report and its implementation retained Cheshire as an administrative county.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Through the Local Government Act 1972, which came into effect on 1 April 1974, some areas in the north became part of the metropolitan counties of Greater Manchester and Merseyside.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Stockport (previously a county borough), Altrincham, Hyde, Dukinfield and Stalybridge in the north-east became part of Greater Manchester.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Much of the Wirral Peninsula in the north-west, including the county boroughs of Birkenhead and Wallasey, joined Merseyside as the Metropolitan Borough of Wirral.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] At the same time the Tintwistle Rural District was transferred to Derbyshire.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The area of south Lancashire not included within either the Merseyside or Greater Manchester counties, including Widnes and the county borough of Warrington, was added to the new non-metropolitan county of Cheshire.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Halton and Warrington became unitary authorities independent of Cheshire County Council on 1 April 1998, but remain part of Cheshire for ceremonial purposes and also for fire and policing.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Halton is part of Liverpool City Region combined authority, which also includes the five metropolitan boroughs of Merseyside.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] A referendum for a further local government reform connected with an elected regional assembly was planned for 2004, but was abandoned following the decisive 'no' vote in a similar referendum in North East England.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] As part of the local government restructuring in April 2009, Cheshire County Council and the Cheshire districts were abolished and replaced by two new unitary authorities, Cheshire East and Cheshire West and Chester.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The existing unitary authorities of Halton and Warrington were not affected by the change.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Cheshire has no county-wide elected local council, but it does have a Lord Lieutenant under the Lieutenancies Act 1997 and a High Sheriff under the Sheriffs Act 1887.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Local government functions apart from the Police and Fire/Rescue services are carried out by four smaller unitary authorities: Cheshire East, Cheshire West and Chester, Halton, and Warrington.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] All four unitary authority areas have borough status.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Policing and fire and rescue services are still provided across the county as a whole.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The Cheshire Fire Authority consist of members of the four councils, while governance of Cheshire Constabulary is performed by the elected Cheshire Police and Crime Commissioner.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Winsford is a major administrative hub for Cheshire with the Police and Fire & Rescue Headquarters based in the town as well as a majority of Cheshire West and Chester Council.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] It was also home to the former Vale Royal Borough Council and Cheshire County Council.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Devolution talks for the county were scheduled for Autumn 2024.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Halton Borough Council has been a member of the Liverpool City Region Combined Authority since that authority was established in 2014.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The Cheshire and Warrington Combined Authority, which includes Cheshire East Council, Cheshire West and Chester Council, and Warrington Borough Council, was established in February 2026 and will hold its first elections in May 2027.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] From 1 April 1974 the area under the control of the county council was divided into eight local government districts; Chester, Congleton, Crewe and Nantwich, Ellesmere Port and Neston, Halton, Macclesfield, Vale Royal and Warrington.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Halton (which includes the towns of Runcorn and Widnes) and Warrington became unitary authorities in 1998.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The remaining districts and the county were abolished as part of local government restructuring on 1 April 2009.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The Halton and Warrington boroughs were not affected by the 2009 restructuring.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] On 25 July 2007, the Secretary of State Hazel Blears announced she was 'minded' to split Cheshire into two new unitary authorities, Cheshire West and Chester, and Cheshire East.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] She confirmed she had not changed her mind on 19 December 2007 and therefore the proposal to split two-tier Cheshire into two would proceed.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Cheshire County Council leader Paul Findlow, who attempted High Court legal action against the proposal, claimed that splitting Cheshire would only disrupt excellent services while increasing living costs for all.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] On 31 January 2008 *The Standard*, Cheshire and district's newspaper, announced that the legal action had been dropped.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Members against the proposal were advised that they may be unable to persuade the court that the decision of Hazel Blears was "manifestly absurd".
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The Cheshire West and Chester unitary authority covers the area formerly occupied by the City of Chester and the boroughs of Ellesmere Port and Neston and Vale Royal; Cheshire East now covers the area formerly occupied by the boroughs of Congleton, Crewe and Nantwich, and Macclesfield.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The changes were implemented on 1 April 2009.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Congleton Borough Council pursued an appeal against the judicial review it lost in October 2007.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The appeal was dismissed on 4 March 2008.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] A plain of glacial till and other glacio-fluvial sediments extends across much of Cheshire, separating the hills of North Wales and the Pennines.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Known as the Cheshire Plain, it was formed following the retreat of a Quaternary ice sheet which left the area dotted with kettle holes, those which hold water being referred to as meres.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The bedrock of this region is almost entirely Triassic sandstone, outcrops of which have long been quarried, notably at Runcorn, providing the distinctive red stone for Liverpool Cathedral and Chester Cathedral.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The eastern half of the county is Upper Triassic Mercia Mudstone laid down with large salt deposits which were mined for hundreds of years around Winsford.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Separating this area from Lower Triassic Sherwood Sandstone to the west is a prominent sandstone ridge known as the Mid Cheshire Ridge.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] A 55-kilometre (34 mi) footpath, the Sandstone Trail, follows this ridge from Frodsham to Whitchurch passing Delamere Forest, Beeston Castle and earlier Iron Age forts.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The western fringes of the Peak District - the southernmost extent of the Pennine range - form the eastern part of the county.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The highest point (county top) in the historic county of Cheshire was Black Hill (582 m (1,909 ft)) near Crowden in the Cheshire Panhandle, a long eastern projection of the county which formerly stretched along the northern side of Longdendale and on the border with the West Riding of Yorkshire.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Black Hill is now the highest point in the ceremonial county of West Yorkshire.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Within the current ceremonial county and the unitary authority of Cheshire East the highest point is Shining Tor on the Derbyshire/Cheshire border between Macclesfield and Buxton, at 559 metres (1,834 ft) above sea level.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] After Shining Tor, the next highest point in Cheshire is Shutlingsloe, at 506 metres (1,660 ft) above sea level.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Shutlingsloe lies just to the south of Macclesfield Forest and is sometimes humorously referred to as the "Matterhorn of Cheshire" thanks to its distinctive steep profile.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The North Cheshire Green Belt is contiguous with the Peak District Park boundary inside Cheshire.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The ceremonial county borders Merseyside, Greater Manchester, Derbyshire, Staffordshire and Shropshire in England along with Flintshire and Wrexham in Wales, arranged by compass directions as shown in the table below.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Cheshire also forms part of the North West England region.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] In July 2022, Eurasian beavers bred in Cheshire for the first time in 400 years, following a reintroduction scheme.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Based on the Census of 2001, the overall population of Cheshire East and Cheshire West and Chester is 673,781, of which 51.3% of the population were male and 48.7% were female.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Of those aged between 0–14 years, 51.5% were male and 48.4% were female; and of those aged over 75 years, 62.9% were female and 37.1% were male.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] This increased to 699,735 at the 2011 Census.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The population for 2021 is forecast to be 708,000.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] In 2001, the population density of Cheshire East and Cheshire West and Chester was 32 people per km2, lower than the North West average of 42 people/km2 and the England and Wales average of 38 people/km2.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Ellesmere Port and Neston had a greater urban density than the rest of the county with 92 people/km2.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] In 2001, ethnic white groups accounted for 98% (662,794) of the population, and 10,994 (2%) in ethnic groups other than white.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] In the 2001 Census, 81% of the population (542,413) identified themselves as Christian; 124,677 (19%) did not identify with any religion or did not answer the question; 5,665 (1%) identified themselves as belonging to other major world religions; and 1,033 belonged to other religions.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The boundary of the Church of England Diocese of Chester follows most closely the pre-1974 county boundary of Cheshire, so it includes all of Wirral, Stockport, and the Cheshire panhandle that included Tintwistle Rural District council area.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] In terms of Roman Catholic church administration, most of Cheshire falls into the Roman Catholic Diocese of Shrewsbury.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Cheshire has a diverse economy with significant sectors including agriculture, automotive, bio-technology, chemical, financial services, food and drink, ICT, and tourism.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The county is famous for the production of Cheshire cheese, salt and silk.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The county has seen a number of inventions and firsts in its history.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] A mainly rural county, Cheshire has a high concentration of villages.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Agriculture is generally based on the dairy trade, and cattle are the predominant livestock.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Land use given to agriculture has fluctuated somewhat, and in 2005 totalled 1558 km2 over 4,609 holdings.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Based on holdings by EC farm type in 2005, 8.51 km2 was allocated to dairy farming, with another 11.78 km2 allocated to cattle and sheep.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The chemical industry in Cheshire was founded in Roman times, with the mining of salt in Winsford, Middlewich and Northwich.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Salt is still mined in the area by British Salt.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The salt mining has led to a continued chemical industry around Northwich, with Brunner Mond based in the town.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Other chemical companies, including Ineos (formerly ICI), have plants at Runcorn.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The Essar Refinery (formerly Shell Stanlow Refinery) is at Ellesmere Port.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The oil refinery has operated since 1924 and has a capacity of 12 million tonnes per year.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Crewe was once the centre of the British railway industry, and remains a major railway junction.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The Crewe railway works, built in 1840, employed 20,000 people at its peak, although the workforce is now less than 1,000.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Also within Cheshire are manufacturing plants for Jaguar and Vauxhall Motors in Ellesmere Port.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The county also has an aircraft industry.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] On the Cheshire border with Flintshire is the Broughton aircraft factory, more recently associated with Airbus.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] For nearly 80 years until it closed in 2011, aircraft were designed and built at Woodford Aerodrome, including Avro Lancaster and Avro Vulcan bombers and the Hawker-Siddeley Nimrod.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Tourism in Cheshire from within the UK and overseas continues to perform strongly.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Over 8 million nights of accommodation (both UK and overseas) and over 2.8 million visits to Cheshire were recorded during 2003.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] At the start of 2003, there were 22,020 VAT-registered enterprises in Cheshire, an increase of 7% since 1998, many in the business services (31.9%) and wholesale/retail (21.7%) sectors.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Between 2002 and 2003 the number of businesses grew in four sectors: public administration and other services (6.0%), hotels and restaurants (5.1%), construction (1.7%), and business services (1.0%).
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The county saw the largest proportional reduction between 2001 and 2002 in employment in the energy and water sector and there was also a significant reduction in the manufacturing sector.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The largest growth during this period was in the other services and distribution, hotels and retail sectors.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Cheshire is considered to be an affluent county.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] However, towns such as Crewe and Winsford have significant deprivation.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The county's proximity to the cities of Manchester and Liverpool means counter urbanisation is common.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Cheshire West has a fairly large proportion of residents who work in Liverpool and Manchester, while the town of Northwich and area of Cheshire East falls more within Manchester's sphere of influence.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] All four local education authorities in Cheshire operate only comprehensive state school systems.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] When Altrincham, Sale and Bebington were moved from Cheshire to Trafford and Merseyside in 1974, they took some former Cheshire selective schools.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] There are two universities based in the county, the University of Chester and the Chester campus of The University of Law.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The Crewe campus of Manchester Metropolitan University was scheduled to close in 2019.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Actors from Cheshire include Russ Abbot, Warren Brown, Julia Chan, Ray Coulthard, Daniel Craig, Tim Curry, Wendy Hiller, Tom Hughes, Tim McInnerny, Ben Miller, Pete Postlethwaite, Adam Rickitt, John Steiner, and Ann Todd.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The most famous author from the county is Lewis Carroll, who wrote *Alice's Adventures in Wonderland* and named the Cheshire Cat character after it.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Other notable Cheshire writers include Hall Caine, Alan Garner, and Elizabeth Gaskell.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Artists from Cheshire include ceramic artist Emma Bossons and sculptor/photographer Andy Goldsworthy.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Local news and television programmes are provided by BBC North West and ITV Granada.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Television signals are received from the Winter Hill TV transmitter.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Local radio stations in the county include Chester's Dee Radio, Capital North West and Wales, Smooth Wales, Cheshire's Silk Radio and Hits Radio Staffordshire & Cheshire.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The BBC directs readers to Stoke and Staffordshire when Cheshire is selected on their website.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] There were plans to launch BBC Radio Cheshire, but those were shelved in 2007 after the BBC licence fee settlement was lower than expected.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Athletes native to Cheshire include sailor Ben Ainslie, cricketer Ian Botham, rock climber Shauna Coxsey, boxer Tyson Fury, oarsman Matt Langridge, mountaineer George Mallory, marathon runner Paula Radcliffe, cyclist Sarah Storey, and hurdler Shirley Strong.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] It has also been home to numerous athletes from outside the county.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Many Premier League footballers have relocated there over the years upon joining nearby teams such as Manchester United F.C., Manchester City F.C., Everton F.C., and Liverpool F.C..
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] These include Dean Ashton, Seth Johnson, Jesse Lingard and Michael Owen.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The "Cheshire Golden Triangle" is the collective name for a group of adjacent Cheshire villages where the number of footballers, actors, and entrepreneurs moving in over the years led to the average house prices becoming some of the most expensive in the UK.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Cheshire has one Football League team, Crewe Alexandra, which plays in EFL League Two.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The next highest-placed teams are Chester, Warrington Town and Macclesfield, who compete in the National League North, the sixth tier of English football.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Macclesfield Town, a former League club, went into liquidation in 2020; a phoenix club, Macclesfield F.C., was formed in 2021, and was promoted to the National League North in 2025.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Northwich Victoria, another ex-League team and founding member of the Football League Division Two in 1892/1893, now represents Cheshire in the Northern Premier League along with Nantwich Town.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The Warrington Wolves and Widnes Vikings are the premier rugby league teams in Cheshire; the former plays in the Super League, while the latter plays in the Championship.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] There are also numerous junior clubs in the county, including Chester Gladiators.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Cheshire County Cricket Club is one of the clubs that make up the minor counties of English and Welsh cricket.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Cheshire also is represented in the highest level basketball league in the UK, the BBL, by Cheshire Phoenix (formerly Cheshire Jets).
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Europe's largest motorcycle event, the Thundersprint, is held in Northwich every May.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The Royal Cheshire Show, an annual agricultural show, has taken place since the 1800s.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Cheshire also produced a military hero in Norman Cyril Jones, a World War I flying ace who won the Distinguished Flying Cross.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] As part of a 2002 marketing campaign, the plant conservation charity Plantlife chose the cuckooflower as the county flower.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Previously, a sheaf of golden wheat was the county emblem, a reference to the Earl of Chester's arms in use from the 12th century.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Prehistoric burial grounds have been discovered at The Bridestones near Congleton (Neolithic) and Robin Hood's Tump near Alpraham (Bronze Age).
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The remains of Iron Age hill forts are found on sandstone ridges at several locations in Cheshire.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Examples include Maiden Castle on Bickerton Hill, Helsby Hillfort and Woodhouse Hillfort at Frodsham.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The Roman fortress and walls of Chester, perhaps the earliest building works in Cheshire remaining above ground, are constructed from purple-grey sandstone.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The distinctive local red sandstone has been used for many monumental and ecclesiastical buildings throughout the county: for example, the medieval Beeston Castle, Chester Cathedral and numerous parish churches.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Occasional residential and industrial buildings, such as Helsby railway station (1849), are also in this sandstone.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Many surviving buildings from the 15th to 17th centuries are timbered, particularly in the southern part of the county.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Notable examples include the moated manor house Little Moreton Hall, dating from around 1450, and many commercial and residential buildings in Chester, Nantwich and surrounding villages.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Early brick buildings include Peover Hall near Macclesfield (1585), Tattenhall Hall (pre-1622), and the Pied Bull Hotel in Chester (17th-century).
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] From the 18th century, orange, red or brown brick became the predominant building material used in Cheshire, although earlier buildings are often faced or dressed with stone.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Examples from the Victorian period onwards often employ distinctive brick detailing, such as brick patterning and ornate chimney stacks and gables.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Notable examples include Arley Hall near Northwich, Willington Hall near Chester (both by Nantwich architect George Latham) and Overleigh Lodge, Chester.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] From the Victorian era, brick buildings often incorporate timberwork in a mock Tudor style, and this hybrid style has been used in some modern residential developments in the county.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Industrial buildings, such as the Macclesfield silk mills (for example, Waters Green New Mill), are also usually in brick.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The county is home to some of the most affluent areas of northern England, including Alderley Edge, Wilmslow, Prestbury, Tarporley and Knutsford, named in 2006 as the most expensive place to buy a house in the north of England.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The former Cheshire town of Altrincham was in second place.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The area is sometimes referred to as The Golden Triangle on account of the area in and around the aforementioned towns and villages.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Holmes Chapel has increasingly become a sought out tourist destination due to being the former hometown of celebrity Harry Styles, and is also undergoing a planned population increase.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Thingwall, currently in the county of Merseyside but historically part of Cheshire until 1974, is known for having once been the base of a Viking parliament established by Norse settlers in the area.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] There is currently one city in the county officially, Chester.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] However, it remains a disputed piece of folklore that the village of Thelwall (today administratively paired with its neighbour Grappenhall in a civil parish) was at one time considered a city.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Warrington is currently the largest urban settlement in the county overall despite its town status, and was one of the third wave of post-Second World War UK new towns designated for expansion.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The main railway line through the county is the West Coast Main Line.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Trains on the main London to Scotland line call at Crewe (in the south of the county) and Warrington Bank Quay (in the north of the county).
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Trains stop at Crewe and Runcorn on the Liverpool branch of the WCML; Crewe and Macclesfield are each hourly stops on the two Manchester branches.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] In the east of Cheshire, Macclesfield station is served by Avanti West Coast, CrossCountry and Northern, on the Manchester–London line.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Services from Manchester to the south coast frequently stop at Macclesfield.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Neston on the Wirral Peninsula is served by a railway station on the Borderlands line between Bidston and Wrexham.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Cheshire has 3,417 miles (5,499 km) of roads, including 214 miles (344 km) of the M6, M62, M53 and M56 motorways; there are 23 interchanges and four service areas.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] It also has the A580 "East Lancashire Road" at its border with Greater Manchester at Leigh.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The M6 motorway at the Thelwall Viaduct carries 140,000 vehicles every 24 hours.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Bus transport in Cheshire is provided by various operators.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The major bus operator in the Cheshire area is D&G Bus.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Other operators in Cheshire include Stagecoach Chester & Wirral and Warrington's Own Buses.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] There are also several operators based outside of Cheshire, who either run services wholly within the area or services which start from outside the area.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Companies include Arriva Buses Wales, Aimee's Travel, High Peak, Metroline Manchester, D&G bus and Stagecoach Manchester.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Some services are run under contract to Cheshire West and Chester, Cheshire East, Borough of Halton and Warrington Councils.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The Cheshire canal system includes several canals originally used to transport the county's industrial products (mostly chemicals).
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] Nowadays they are mainly used for tourist traffic.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The Cheshire Ring is formed from the Rochdale, Ashton, Peak Forest, Macclesfield, Trent and Mersey and Bridgewater canals.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The Manchester Ship Canal is a wide, 36-mile (58 km) stretch of water opened in 1894.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] It consists of the rivers Irwell and Mersey made navigable to Manchester for seagoing ships leaving the Mersey estuary.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/cheshire] The canal passes through the north of the county via Runcorn and Warrington.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] The charity's flagship event is an annual telethon broadcast usually on the third Friday evening of November on BBC One and BBC Two.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] Pudsey Bear has served as its mascot, while the late Sir Terry Wogan hosted the event for 35 years.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] As a cornerstone of British television, Children in Need is one of the UK's two major telethons, alongside Comic Relief's Red Nose Day.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] It remains the BBC's sole in-house charity.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] Originally broadcast from the BBC Television Centre, the telethon relocated to the BBC Elstree Centre between 2013 and 2020 following the closure of the former.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] Historically lasting up to seven hours, the event was streamlined to a three-hour programme (7:00 pm to 10:00 pm) from 2020 onwards.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] To accommodate family-friendly content, the television watershed is postponed until 11:30 pm on the night of the broadcast.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] The 2020 telethon, impacted by the COVID-19 pandemic, featured a significantly reduced format with just four presenters: Mel Giedroyc, Alex Scott, Chris Ramsey, and Stephen Mangan.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] Since November 2021, the event has been staged at Dock10, MediaCityUK in Salford.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] In October 2023, it was announced that Lenny Rush—a children's television star and future *Doctor Who* actor—would become the first child co-presenter in the charity's history during the 2023 appeal broadcast.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] In October 2025, it was announced that Paddy McGuinness and TV personality and British rapper Big Zuu would debut in the presenting line-up for the 2025 appeal show.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] The BBC's inaugural charity appeal was a five-minute radio broadcast on Christmas Day 1927, raising approximately £1,342 for four children's charities.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] The first televised appeal, the *Children's Hour*, aired in 1955.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] Fronted by Harry Corbett and the yellow glove puppet Sooty Bear, these appeals continued annually on television and radio until 1979, raising a total of £625,836.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] Sir Terry Wogan made his debut during the five-minute appeal in 1978 and returned in 1979.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] Animated characters such as Peter Pan and Tom and Jerry occasionally featured in these broadcasts.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] The first dedicated *Children in Need* telethon aired in 1980, replacing standard continuity segments with fundraising appeals during evening programming.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] Presented by Terry Wogan, Sue Lawley, and Esther Rantzen, the event raised £1 million, exclusively for UK-based children's charities—a significant increase from previous campaigns.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] By 1984, the telethon evolved into a single continuous programme, abandoning regular programming slots.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] The format expanded to include radio and online content, with Wogan remaining the primary host until 2014.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] In 2007, it was reported that Wogan had received an annual honorarium since 1980 (amounting to £9,065 in 2005); the BBC stated that the payment came from BBC resources rather than from the *Children in Need* charity fund.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] Two days before the 2007 event, Wogan waived his fee.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] He stepped down due to health issues and died in 2016.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] In 1988, BBC *Children in Need* registered as a charity in England and Wales (no.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] A notable partnership in 2020 saw the charity collaborate with the McLaren Formula One Team at a race to support initiatives in Turkey.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] In November 2006, *Children in Need* faced public criticism after Intelligent Giving published an article, titled "Four Things Wrong with Pudsey", which questioned the efficiency of its grant-giving model and the quality of some of its public reporting as "shambolic".
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] Simon Antrobus has served as chief executive since 2016.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] Corporate partners have played a key role in fundraising.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] Asda, McDonald's, One Stop, Greggs, Enterprise, and Cineworld are among the charity's longstanding sponsors.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] Welcome Break—whose service stations host outlets such as WHSmith, Waitrose, Subway, Burger King, Pret a Manger, Starbucks and Harry Ramsden's—has also supported the cause.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] The 2025 Sidemen Charity Match, scheduled for Wembley Stadium, will raise funds for *Children in Need*.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] A former BBC governor said that Jimmy Savile was kept away from *Children in Need*.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] Sir Roger Jones who was also chairman of the charity said he had suspicions about Savile a decade before the news of Savile's sexual abuse scandal came to public light in 2012.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] His comments came on the day an inquiry began into whether the BBC's child protection and whistle-blowing policies were acceptable.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] In November 2006, Intelligent Giving published an article about *Children in Need*, which attracted wide attention across the British media.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] The article, titled "Four Things Wrong with Pudsey", described donations to *Children in Need* as a "lazy and inefficient way of giving" and pointed out that, as a grant-giving charity, *Children in Need* would use donations to pay two sets of administration costs.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] It also described the quality of some of its public reporting as "shambolic".
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] In 2007, it was reported that presenter Terry Wogan had been receiving an annual honorarium since 1980 (amounting to £9,065 in 2005).
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] This made him the only celebrity paid for his participation in *Children in Need*.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] According to Wogan's account, he would "quite happily do it for nothing" and had "never asked for a fee".
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] The BBC stated that the amount, which was paid from BBC resources rather than from the *Children in Need* charity fund, had "never been negotiated", having instead increased in line with inflation.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] There has been concern about the type of groups receiving funding from *Children in Need*.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] Writing in *The Spectator*, Ross Clark noted that funding goes towards controversial groups such as Women in Prison, which campaigns against jailing female criminals.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] Another charity highlighted was the Children's Legal Centre, which provided funding for Shabina Begum to sue her school as she wanted to wear the jilbāb.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] Clark pondered whether donors seeing cancer victims on screen would appreciate "that a slice of their donation would be going into the pockets of Cherie Blair to help a teenage girl sue her school over her refusal to wear a school uniform".
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] During November 2024, Rosie Millard stepped down as Chair of BBC *Children in Need* after protesting over grants awarded to an LGBT youth charity whose former chief had been involved in a child abuse scandal.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] The Sir Terry Wogan Fundraiser of the Year has been awarded annually since 2016 to individuals demonstrating exceptional commitment to raising funds for BBC *Children in Need*.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] Established by Wogan's family in memory of the late Sir Terry Wogan—the charity's long-standing host—the award was first presented by his son, Mark, during the 2016 telethon.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] Subsequent ceremonies have featured notable presenters, including Joanna Lumley (2017) and Michael Ball (2021).
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] The telethon features performances by prominent singers, musical groups, and celebrities, often participating in sketches or musical numbers during the 6.5-hour-long programme.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] Notable appearances include actors from ITV programmes—sometimes in character or from their show's sets—as well as BBC newsreaders, whose performances became an annual tradition.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] Stars of West End musicals frequently perform excerpts from their productions after their theatre curtain calls.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] BBC One dedicates its entire evening schedule to the telethon, pausing only for a 35-minute break at 10:00 pm to air *BBC News at Ten*, weather updates, and regional news.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] Simultaneously, BBC Two broadcasts complementary programming, such as *Mastermind Children in Need*, which is a form of *Celebrity Mastermind*.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] Pre-telethon specials include *DIY SOS: The Big Build*, *Bargain Hunt*, and *The One Show*, featuring challenges like the hosts' rickshaw ride and a celebrity edition of *Pointless* hosted by Alexander Armstrong and Richard Osman, assisted by Pudsey Bear.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] Regional contributions play a significant role: BBC England's regions provide hourly 5–8-minute updates, while BBC Scotland, BBC Cymru Wales, and BBC Northern Ireland historically aired extended local segments before rejoining the network broadcast around 1:00 am.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] From 2010, however, these nations adopted the English regions' hourly update format.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] Since 2011, a central feature of the telethon has been a live choir performance involving more than 1,000 children across 8–10 UK locations, singing in unison.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] The mascot fronting the *Children in Need* appeal is called Pudsey Bear.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] He was created and named in 1985 by BBC graphic designer Joanna Lane, who worked in the BBC's design department.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] Asked to revamp the logo, with a brief to improve the charity's image, Lane said "It was like a lightbulb moment for me.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] We were bouncing ideas off each other and I latched on to this idea of a teddy bear.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] I immediately realised there was a huge potential for a mascot beyond the 2D logo".
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] The bear was named after her hometown of Pudsey, West Yorkshire, where her grandfather was mayor.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] A reproduction of the bear mascot (made of vegetation) is in Pudsey park, near the town centre.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] Originally introduced for the 1985 appeal, Pudsey Bear was created as a triangular shaped logo, depicting a yellow-orange teddy bear with a red bandana tied over one eye.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] The bandana had a pattern of small black triangles.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] The mouth of the bear depicted a sad expression.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] The lettering "BBC" appeared as 3 circular black buttons running vertically down the front of the bear, one capital letter on each, in white.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] Perpendicular to the buttons, the words "children-in-need" appeared in all lower case letters along the base of the triangular outline.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] Accessibility for young readers, and people with disabilities including speech and reading challenges, were factors weighed by the designer Joanna Ball, specifically the "P" sound in "Pudsey" name, and the choice of all lower case sans serif letters for the logotype.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] The original design was adapted for various applications for use in the 1985 appeal in both 2D graphics and 3D objects.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] Items using the original 1985 design included a filmed opening title sequence, using cartoon cell animation, a postage stamp, and a prototype soft toy, commissioned from a film and TV prop maker (citation).
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] The original prototype soft toy was orange and reflected the design of the logo, which was then adapted for approximately 12 identical bears, one for each regional BBC Television Studio.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] These bears were numbered and tagged with the official logo and auctioned off as part of the appeal.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] The number 1 Pudsey Bear was allocated to the Leeds region.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] Joanna Lumley appeared with one of the soft toys during the opening of Blackpool Illuminations and named Pudsey Bear the official mascot of the BBC *Children in Need* appeal.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] Whilst retaining the concept of a teddy bear with a bandana over one eye, all other elements were changed.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] Specifically, the triangular elements of the underlying design were abandoned, and the corporate identity colour scheme was changed.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] The new bandana design was white with red spots, one of the buttons was removed and the logotype now appeared as building blocks, which spelled out "BBC CHILDREN IN NEED" in capital letters.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] Pudsey now had a smiling expression on his face rather than a sad one in the previous logo.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] In 2007, Pudsey and the logo were redesigned again.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] This time, Pudsey's bandana had multicoloured spots, and all of the buttons were removed.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] By 2009, Pudsey had been joined by another bear, a brown female bear named "Blush".
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] She had a spotty bow with the pattern similar to Pudsey's bandana pattern.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] In 2013, Moshi Monsters introduced Pudsey as an in-game item for 100 Rox.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] The *Children in Need 2015* campaign on 13 November 2015 marked the thirtieth birthday of Pudsey Bear, who has been the charity's mascot since 1985.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] In 2022, as part of the corporate BBC rebrand, the logo was completely redesigned.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] The phrase "CHILDREN IN NEED" in capital letters appeared in a modified rounded version of BBC Reith Sans Bold, and Pudsey Bear was removed as part of the logo.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/children-in-need] Despite this, Pudsey Bear remains in use as a mascot and was also given a redesign which involved making the multicoloured spots on his bandana larger and adding multicoloured spots onto the soles of his now white feet.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/claire-house-children-s-hospice] The hospice helps seriously and terminally ill children and young adults from 0–23 years by providing specialist nursing care and emotional support.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/claire-house-children-s-hospice] It has provided care for children and young people across Merseyside, Cheshire and North Wales since it opened in 1998.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/claire-house-children-s-hospice] The organisation has two sites: a hospice in Bebington, the Wirral, and the Hub in West Derby, Liverpool, that offers day care.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/claire-house-children-s-hospice] Support can be provided at Claire House or at home and can be for the child, young person or for family members.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/claire-house-children-s-hospice] The charity has featured on Children in Need in 2011, 2014 and 2016.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/claire-house-children-s-hospice] It also has high-profile supporters including Steven Gerrard and Wayne Rooney.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/claire-house-children-s-hospice] As of 2017, the charity is providing care for over 200 babies, children and young people and supporting more than 200 bereaved families.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/claire-house-children-s-hospice] In July 2015 Claire House was rated as 'Outstanding' by the Care Quality Commission.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/claire-house-children-s-hospice] Claire House, Wirral is open 24 hours a day, seven days a week and offers a range of services.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/claire-house-children-s-hospice] Children can have fun in the multi-sensory room, art room, hydrotherapy pool and Jacuzzi.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/claire-house-children-s-hospice] There is a separate wing complete with bar, sound system and Xbox for teenagers and young adults.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/claire-house-children-s-hospice] Claire House also provides end of life care, ensuring that a child's last days are as comfortable and memorable as possible.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/claire-house-children-s-hospice] In 2016 the charity occupied a site in West Derby, Liverpool, that used to be a Carmelite Monastery.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/claire-house-children-s-hospice] The Claire House Liverpool Hub opened in the summer of 2017, offering services such as counselling, holistic therapies and hospice to home support.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/claire-house-children-s-hospice] Claire House hopes to one day open a new-state-of-the-art hospice on the site and reach out to more children in Merseyside.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/claire-house-children-s-hospice] Supporters of the charity include the Mowgli Trust which has donated £325,000.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/claire-house-children-s-hospice] The trust was established by Nisha Katona, whose company Mowgli Street Food is headquartered in Liverpool.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] A **geographic coordinate system** (**GCS**) is a spherical or geodetic coordinate system for measuring and communicating positions directly on Earth as latitude and longitude.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] It is the simplest, oldest, and most widely used type of the various spatial reference systems that are in use, and forms the basis for most others.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] Although latitude and longitude form a coordinate tuple like a Cartesian coordinate system, geographic coordinate systems are not Cartesian because the measurements are angles and are not on a planar surface.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] A full GCS specification, such as those listed in the EPSG and ISO 19111 standards, also includes a choice of geodetic datum (including an Earth ellipsoid), as different datums will yield different latitude and longitude values for the same location.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] The invention of a geographic coordinate system is generally credited to Eratosthenes of Cyrene, who composed his now-lost *Geography* at the Library of Alexandria in the 3rd century BC.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] A century later, Hipparchus of Nicaea improved on this system by determining latitude from stellar measurements rather than solar altitude and determining longitude by timings of lunar eclipses, rather than dead reckoning.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] Ptolemy credited him with the full adoption of longitude and latitude, rather than measuring latitude in terms of the length of the midsummer day.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] Ptolemy's 2nd-century *Geography* used the same prime meridian but measured latitude from the Equator instead.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] After their work was translated into Arabic in the 9th century, Al-Khwārizmī's *Book of the Description of the Earth* corrected Marinus' and Ptolemy's errors regarding the length of the Mediterranean Sea, causing medieval Arabic cartography to use a prime meridian around 10° east of Ptolemy's line.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] Mathematical cartography resumed in Europe following Maximus Planudes' recovery of Ptolemy's text a little before 1300; the text was translated into Latin at Florence by Jacopo d'Angelo around 1407.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] In 1884, the United States hosted the International Meridian Conference, attended by representatives from twenty-five nations.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] Twenty-two of them agreed to adopt the longitude of the Royal Observatory in Greenwich, England as the zero-reference line.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] The Dominican Republic voted against the motion, while France and Brazil abstained.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] France adopted Greenwich Mean Time in place of local determinations by the Paris Observatory in 1911.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] The *latitude* φ of a point on Earth's surface is defined in one of three ways, depending on the type of coordinate system.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] In each case, the latitude is the angle formed by the plane of the equator and a line formed by the point on the surface and a second point on equatorial plane.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] The path that joins all points of the same latitude traces a circle on the surface of Earth, as viewed from above the north or south pole, called parallels, as they are parallel to the equator and to each other.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] The north pole is 90° N; the south pole is 90° S.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] The 0° parallel of latitude is defined to be the equator, the fundamental plane of a geographic coordinate system.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] The equator divides the globe into Northern and Southern Hemispheres.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] The *longitude* λ of a point on Earth's surface is the angle east or west of a reference meridian to another meridian that passes through that point.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] All meridians are halves of great ellipses, which converge at the North and South Poles.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] The meridian of the British Royal Observatory in Greenwich, in southeast London, England, is the international prime meridian, although some organizations—such as the French Institut national de l'information géographique et forestière—continue to use other meridians for internal purposes.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] The antipodal meridian of Greenwich is both 180°W and 180°E.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] This is not to be conflated with the International Date Line, which partly overlaps with the 180° meridian but diverges from it in several places for political and convenience reasons, including between far eastern Russia and the far western Aleutian Islands.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] The combination of these two components specifies the position of any location on the surface of Earth, without consideration of altitude or depth.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] The visual grid on a map formed by lines of latitude and longitude is known as a *graticule*.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] The origin/zero point of this system is located in the Gulf of Guinea about 625 km (390 mi) south of Tema, Ghana, a location often facetiously called Null Island.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] In order to use the theoretical definitions of latitude, longitude, and height to precisely measure actual locations on the physical earth, a *geodetic datum* must be used.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] A *horizonal datum* is used to precisely measure latitude and longitude, while a *vertical datum* is used to measure elevation or altitude.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] Both types of datum bind a mathematical model of the shape of the earth (usually a reference ellipsoid for a horizontal datum, and a more precise geoid for a vertical datum) to the earth.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] Traditionally, this binding was created by a network of control points, surveyed locations at which monuments are installed, and were only accurate for a region of the surface of the Earth.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] Newer datums are based on a global network for satellite measurements (GNSS, VLBI, SLR and DORIS).
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] This combination of a mathematical model and physical binding ensures that users of the same datum obtain identical coordinates for a given physical point.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] However, different datums typically produce different coordinates for the same location (sometimes deviating several hundred meters) not due to actual movement, but because the reference system itself is shifted.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] Because any spatial reference system or map projection is ultimately calculated from latitude and longitude, it is crucial that they clearly state the datum on which they are based.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] For example, a UTM coordinate based on a WGS84 realisation will be different than a UTM coordinate based on NAD27 for the same location.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] Transforming coordinates from one datum to another requires a datum transformation method such as a Helmert transformation, although in certain situations a simple translation may be sufficient.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] Datums may be global, meaning that they represent the whole Earth, or they may be regional, meaning that they represent an ellipsoid best-fit to only a portion of the Earth.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] Datums with a regional fit of the ellipsoid that are chosen by a national cartographical organization include the North American Datums, the European ED50, and the British OSGB36.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] Given a location, the datum provides the latitude $\phi$ and longitude $\lambda$ .
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] In the United Kingdom there are three common latitude, longitude, and height systems in use.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] WGS 84 differs at Greenwich from the one used on published maps OSGB36 by approximately 112 m.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] Points on the Earth's surface move relative to each other due to continental plate motion, subsidence, and diurnal Earth tidal movement caused by the Moon and the Sun.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] This daily movement can be as much as a meter.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] Continental movement can be up to 10 cm a year, or 10 m in a century.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] A weather system high-pressure area can cause a sinking of 5 mm.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] Scandinavia is rising by 1 cm a year as a result of the melting of the ice sheets of the last ice age, but neighboring Scotland is rising by only 0.2 cm.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] These changes are insignificant if a regional datum is used, but are statistically significant if a global datum is used.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] On the GRS 80 or WGS 84 spheroid at sea level at the Equator, one latitudinal second measures 30.715 m, one latitudinal minute is 1843 m and one latitudinal degree is 110.6 km.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] The circles of longitude, meridians, meet at the geographical poles, with the west–east width of a second naturally decreasing as latitude increases.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] On the Equator at sea level, one longitudinal second measures 30.92 m, a longitudinal minute is 1855 m and a longitudinal degree is 111.3 km.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] The returned measure of meters per degree latitude varies continuously with latitude.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] The formulae both return units of meters per degree.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] ( $\textstyle {\beta }\,\!$ is known as the reduced (or parametric) latitude).
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] Aside from rounding, this is the exact distance along a parallel of latitude; getting the distance along the shortest route will be more work, but those two distances are always within 0.6 m of each other if the two points are one degree of longitude apart.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] Like any series of multiple-digit numbers, latitude-longitude pairs can be challenging to communicate and remember.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/geographic-coordinate-system] These are not distinct coordinate systems, only alternative methods for expressing latitude and longitude measurements.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-echo] The ***Liverpool Echo*** is a local newspaper published by Reach plc and based in Liverpool, England.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-echo] It is published Monday through Sunday, and is Liverpool's daily newspaper.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-echo] Until January 13, 2012, it had a sister morning paper, the *Liverpool Daily Post*.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-echo] Between July and December 2025, it had an average daily circulation of 7,645.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-echo] Historically, the newspaper was published by the Liverpool Daily Post & Echo Ltd.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-echo] Its office is in St Paul's Square, Liverpool, having downsized from Old Hall Street in March 2018.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-echo] In 1879, the *Liverpool Echo* was published as a cheaper sister paper to the *Liverpool Daily Post*.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-echo] From its inception until 1917 the newspaper cost a halfpenny.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-echo] It is now £1.40p Monday to Friday, £1.80p on Saturday and £1.40p on Sunday.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-echo] In 1973, the paper moved from Victoria Street to a building in Old Hall Street.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-echo] The limited company expanded internationally and underwent restructuring in 1985, becoming Trinity International Holdings Plc.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-echo] Prior to this restructuring, the two original newspapers had recently been re-launched in tabloid format.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-echo] A special Sunday edition of the *Echo* was published on 16 April 1989, for reporting on the previous day's Hillsborough disaster, in which 97 Liverpool F.C. fans were fatally injured at the FA Cup semi-final tie in Sheffield.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-echo] All of the 75,000 copies printed were sold.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-echo] In 1999 Trinity merged with Mirror Group Newspapers to become Trinity Mirror, the largest stable of newspapers in the country.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-echo] In 2018, Trinity Mirror was rebranded as Reach plc.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-echo] On 7 January 2014 it was announced that a regular Sunday edition of the paper would be launched.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-echo] The *Sunday Echo* is "a seventh day of publication, not an independent product", according to the paper.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-echo] In 2008 the paper moved printing from Liverpool to Trinity Mirror Plc, Oldham, Greater Manchester, while journalists remain based at St Paul's Square in Liverpool city centre, where they had relocated to in 2018.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-echo] In 2020, editor-in-chief Alistair Machray stood down and was replaced by Maria Breslin.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-echo] Criticism has been directed at the *Echo* for its perceived bias towards local politicians.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-echo] In 2024, Liam Thorp, the paper's political editor, collaborated on a book titled "Head North: A Rallying Cry for a More Equal Britain" with the metro mayors of Manchester and Liverpool, Andy Burnham and Steve Rotheram.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Established as a borough in Lancashire in 1207, Liverpool became significant in the late 17th century when the Port of Liverpool was heavily involved in the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The port also imported cotton for the Lancashire textile mills, and became a major departure point for English and Irish emigrants to North America.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] It entered a period of decline in the mid-20th century, which was largely reversed after the European Union selected it as the European Capital of Culture for 2008, reportedly generating over £800 million for the local economy within a year.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The economy of Liverpool is diverse and encompasses tourism, culture, maritime, hospitality, healthcare, life sciences, advanced manufacturing, creative and digital sectors.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The city is home to the UK's second highest number of art galleries, national museums, listed buildings, and parks and open spaces, behind only London.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] It is often used as a filming location due to its architecture and was the fifth most visited UK city by foreign tourists in 2022.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] It has produced numerous musicians, most notably the Beatles, and recording artists from the city have had more UK No.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] 1 singles than anywhere else in the world.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] It has also produced numerous academics, actors, artists, comedians, filmmakers, poets, scientists, sportspeople, and writers.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] It is the home of Premier League football teams Everton and Liverpool.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The world's oldest still-operating main line railway station, Liverpool Lime Street, is in the city centre; it is also served by the underground Merseyrail network.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The city's port was the fourth largest in the UK in 2023, with numerous shipping and freight lines having headquarters and offices there.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Residents of Liverpool are formally known as Liverpudlians but are more often called Scousers in reference to scouse, a local stew made popular by sailors.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The city's distinct local accent is also primarily known as Scouse.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Its cultural and ethnic diversity is the result of attracting immigrants from various areas, particularly Ireland, Scandinavia, and Wales; it is also home to the UK's oldest black community and Europe's oldest Chinese community, as well as the first mosque in England.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The name comes from the Old English *lifer*, meaning thick or muddy water, and *pōl*, meaning a pool or creek, and is first recorded around 1190 as *Liuerpul*.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] According to the *Cambridge Dictionary of English Place-Names*, "The original reference was to a pool or tidal creek now filled up into which two streams drained".
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Other origins of the name have been suggested, including "elverpool", a reference to the large number of eels in the Mersey.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The adjective "Liverpudlian" was first recorded in 1833.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] In the Middle Ages, Liverpool first existed as farmland within the West Derby Hundred before growing into a small town of farmers, fishermen and tradesmen and tactical army base for King John of England.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] A tidal creek, known as the Pool provided a natural harbour for ships.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The town was planned with its own castle, although due to outbreaks of disease and its subordinance to the nearby Roman port of Chester, the town's growth and prosperity stagnated until the late 17th and early 18th centuries.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] There was substantial growth in the mid- to late 18th century, when the town became the European port most heavily involved in the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] King John's letters patent of 1207 announced the foundation of the borough of Liverpool (then spelt as *Liuerpul*).
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] There is no evidence that the place had previously been a centre of any trade.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The borough was probably created because King John decided that it would be a convenient place to embark men and supplies for his Irish campaigns: in particular his Irish campaign of 1209.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The original street plan of Liverpool is said to have been designed by King John near the same time it was granted a royal charter, making it a borough.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The original seven streets were laid out in the shape of a double cross: Bank Street (now Water Street), Castle Street, Chapel Street, Dale Street, Juggler Street (now High Street), Moor Street (now Tithebarn Street) and Whiteacre Street (now Old Hall Street).
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Liverpool Castle was built before 1235, and survived until it was demolished in the 1720s.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] By the middle of the 16th century, the population was still around 600, although this was likely to have fallen from an earlier peak of 1,000 people due to slow trade and the effects of the plague.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] In the 17th century, there was slow progress in trade and population growth.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Battles for control of the town were waged during the English Civil War, including a brief siege in 1644.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] In 1699, the same year as its first recorded slave ship, *Liverpool Merchant*, set sail for Africa, Liverpool was made a parish by Act of Parliament.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] But arguably, the legislation of 1695 that reformed the Liverpool council was of more significance to its subsequent development.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Since Roman times nearby Chester on the River Dee had been the region's principal port on the Irish Sea.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] However, as the Dee began to silt up, maritime trade from Chester became increasingly difficult and shifted towards Liverpool on the neighbouring River Mersey.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The first of the Liverpool docks was constructed in 1715, and the system of docks gradually grew into a large interconnected system.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] As trade from the West Indies, including sugar, surpassed that of Ireland and Europe, and as the River Dee continued to silt up, Liverpool began to grow even faster.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The first commercial wet dock was built in Liverpool in 1715.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Substantial profits from the slave trade and tobacco helped the town to prosper and rapidly grow, although several prominent local men, including William Rathbone, William Roscoe and Edward Rushton, were at the forefront of the local abolitionist movement.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The 19th century saw Liverpool rise to global economic importance.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Pioneering arose, and world-first technology and civic facilities launched in the city to serve the accelerating population, one that was fuelled by an influx of ethnic and religious communities from all around the world.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] By the start of the 19th century, a large volume of trade was passing through Liverpool, and the construction of major buildings reflected this wealth.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] In 1830, Liverpool and Manchester became the first cities to have an intercity rail link, through the Liverpool and Manchester Railway.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The population continued to rise rapidly, especially during the 1840s when Irish migrants began arriving by the hundreds of thousands as a result of the Great Famine.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] While many Irish people settled in the city at that time, a large percentage also emigrated to the United States or moved to the industrial centres of Lancashire, Yorkshire, and the Midlands.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] In her poetical illustration "Liverpool" (1832), which celebrates the city's worldwide commerce, Letitia Elizabeth Landon refers specifically to the Macgregor Laird expedition to the Niger River, at that time in progress.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] This is accompanied by a painting by Samuel Austin, *Liverpool, from the Mersey*.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Britain was a major market for cotton imported from the Deep South of the United States, which fed the textile industry in the country.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Given the crucial place cotton held in the city's economy, during the American Civil War Liverpool was, in the words of historian Sven Beckert, "the most pro-Confederate place in the world outside the Confederacy itself".
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Liverpool merchants helped to bring out cotton from ports blockaded by the Union Navy, built ships of war for the Confederacy, and supplied the South with military equipment and credit.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] During the war, the Confederate Navy ship, the CSS *Alabama*, was built at Birkenhead on the Mersey, and the CSS *Shenandoah* surrendered there (being the final surrender at the end of the war).
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The city was also the centre of Confederate purchases of war materiel, including arms and ammunition, uniforms, and naval supplies to be smuggled by British blockade runners to the South.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] For periods during the 19th century, the wealth of Liverpool exceeded that of London, and Liverpool's Custom House was the single largest contributor to the British Exchequer.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Liverpool was the only British city ever to have its own Whitehall office.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] During this century, at least 40% of the world's entire trade passed through Liverpool.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] In the early 19th century, Liverpool played a major role in the Antarctic sealing industry, in recognition of which Liverpool Beach in the South Shetland Islands is named after the city.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] As early as 1851, the city was described as "the New York of Europe".
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] During the late 19th and early 20th centuries, Liverpool was attracting immigrants from across Europe.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] This resulted in the construction of a diverse array of religious buildings in the city for the new ethnic and religious groups, many of which are still in use today.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The Deutsche Kirche, Greek Orthodox Church of St Nicholas, Gustav Adolf Church and Princes Road Synagogue were all established in the 1800s to serve Liverpool's growing German, Greek, Nordic and Jewish communities, respectively.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] One of Liverpool's oldest surviving churches, St.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Peter's Roman Catholic Church, served the Polish community in its final years as a place of worship.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The 20th century saw Liverpool's established rank as a global economic powerhouse challenged.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Its strategic location as an international seaport made it particularly vulnerable in two World wars.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Economic depressions (both in the United Kingdom and across the world), changing housing patterns and containerisation in the maritime industry contributed to a downtrend in the city's productivity and prosperity.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Despite this, the city's influence on global popular culture excelled and by the end of the century, the continuing process of urban renewal paved the way for the redefined modern city of the 21st century.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The period after the Great War was marked by social unrest, as society grappled with the massive war losses of young men, as well as trying to re-integrate veterans into civilian life and the economy.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Unemployment and poor living standards greeted many ex-servicemen.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Union organising and strikes took place in numerous locations, including a police strike in Liverpool among the City Police.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Numerous colonial soldiers and sailors from Africa and India, who had served with the British Armed Forces, settled in Liverpool and other port cities.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] In June 1919, they were subject to attack by whites in racial riots; residents in the port included Swedish immigrants, and both groups had to compete with native people from Liverpool for jobs and housing.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] In this period, race riots also took place in other port cities.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Act 1919 resulted in mass council housing being built across Liverpool during the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Numerous private homes were also built during this era.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] During the Great Depression of the early 1930s, unemployment peaked at around 30% in the city.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Liverpool was the site of Britain's first provincial airport, operating from 1930.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] During the Second World War, the critical strategic importance of Liverpool was recognised by both Hitler and Churchill.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The city was heavily bombed by the Germans, suffering a blitz second only to London's.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The pivotal Battle of the Atlantic was planned, fought and won from Liverpool.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The *Luftwaffe* made 80 air raids on Merseyside, killing 2,500 people and causing damage to almost half the homes in the metropolitan area.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Significant rebuilding followed the war, including massive housing estates and the Seaforth Dock, the largest dock project in Britain.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Since 1952, Liverpool has been twinned with Cologne, Germany, a city that also suffered severe aerial bombing during the war.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] In the 1950s and 1960s, much of the immediate reconstruction that took place in the city centre proved to be deeply unpopular.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The historic portions of the city that had survived German bombing suffered extensive destruction during urban renewal.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] It has been argued that the so-called "Shankland Plan" of the 1960s, named after the town planner Graeme Shankland, led to compromised town planning and vast road-building schemes that devastated and divided inner city neighbourhoods.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Concrete brutalist architecture, compromised visions, botched projects and grand designs that were never realised became the subject of condemnation.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Historian Raphael Samuel labelled Graeme Shankland "the butcher of Liverpool".
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] A West Indian black community has existed in the city since the first two decades of the 20th century.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Like most British cities and industrialised towns, Liverpool became home to Commonwealth immigrants, beginning after World War I with colonial soldiers and sailors who had served in the area.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] More immigrants arrived after World War II, mostly settling in older inner-city areas such as Toxteth, where housing was less expensive.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The black population of Liverpool was recorded at 1.90% in 2011.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] In the 2021 Census, 5.2% described themselves as black African, Caribbean, mixed white and black African, mixed white and Caribbean or 'other black'.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] In the 1960s, Liverpool was the centre of the "Merseybeat" sound whose best-known band is the Beatles.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Liverpool Airport was renamed after Beatle and Liverpudlian John Lennon in 2002, the first British airport to be named in honour of an individual.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Previously part of Lancashire, and a county borough from 1889, Liverpool became a metropolitan borough within the newly created metropolitan county of Merseyside, in 1974.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] From the mid-1970s onwards, Liverpool's docks and traditional manufacturing industries declined due to restructuring of shipping and heavy industry, causing massive losses of jobs.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The advent of containerisation meant that the city's docks became largely obsolete, and dock workers were made unemployed.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] By the early 1980s, unemployment rates in Liverpool were among the highest in the UK, standing at 17% by January 1982 although, this was about half the level of unemployment that had affected the city during the Great Depression some 50 years previously.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] During this period, Liverpool became a hub of fierce left-wing opposition to the central government in London.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Liverpool in the 1980s has been labelled as Britain's 'shock city'.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Once the acclaimed second city of the British Empire which rivalled the capital city in global significance, Liverpool had collapsed in to its 'nadir' at the depths of post-colonial, post-industrial Britain.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] In the late 20th century, Liverpool's economy began to recover.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The late 1980s saw the opening of a regenerated Albert Dock which proved to be a catalyst for further regeneration.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] In the mid-1990s, the city enjoyed growth rates higher than the national average.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] At the end of the 20th century, Liverpool was concentrating on regeneration, a process that continues today.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Ongoing regeneration combined with the hosting of internationally significant events has helped to re-purpose Liverpool as one of the most visited, tourist orientated, cities in the United Kingdom.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] City leaders are focussing on long-term strategies to grow the city's population and economy, while national government explores the continuous potential for devolution in the city.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] In 2002, Queen Elizabeth II and Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh visited Liverpool to mark the Golden Jubilee.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] On speaking to an audience at Liverpool Town Hall, the Queen recognised Liverpool as "one of the most distinctive and energetic parts of the United Kingdom", and paid tribute to the city's "major orchestras, world-class museums and galleries".
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] She also acknowledged Liverpool's bid to become the European Capital of Culture.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] To celebrate the Golden Jubilee of Elizabeth II in 2002, the conservation charity Plantlife organised a competition to choose county flowers; the sea-holly was Liverpool's final choice.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The initiative was designed to highlight growing threats to the UK's flower species and also ask the public about which flowers best represented their county.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Capitalising on the popularity of 1960s rock groups, such as the Beatles, as well as the city's world-class art galleries, museums and landmarks, tourism and culture have become a significant factor in Liverpool's economy.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] In 2004, property developer Grosvenor started the Paradise Project, a £920 million development based on Paradise Street.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] This produced one of the most significant changes to Liverpool's city centre since the post-war reconstruction.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Renamed as 'Liverpool One,' the centre opened in May 2008.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] In 2007, events and celebrations took place in honour of the 800th anniversary of the founding of the borough of Liverpool.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Liverpool was designated as a joint European Capital of Culture for 2008.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The celebrations included the erection of La Princesse, a large mechanical spider 20 metres high and weighing 37 tonnes, which represented the "eight legs" of Liverpool: honour, history, music, the Mersey, the ports, governance, sunshine and culture.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] La Princesse roamed the streets of the city during the festivities, and concluded by entering the Queensway Tunnel.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Spearheaded by the multi-billion-pound Liverpool ONE development, regeneration continued throughout the 2010s.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Some of the most significant redevelopment projects included new buildings in the Commercial District, King's Dock, Mann Island, around Lime Street, the Baltic Triangle, RopeWalks, and Edge Lane.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Changes to Liverpool's governance took place in 2014.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The local authority of Liverpool City Council decided to pool its power and resources with surrounding boroughs through the formation of the Liverpool City Region Combined Authority in a form of devolution.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] With a devolved budget granted by central government, the authority now oversees and invests in foremost strategic affairs throughout the Liverpool City Region, including major regeneration projects.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The authority, along with Liverpool City Council itself, has embarked on long-term plans to grow the population and economy of the city.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] By the 2020s, urban regeneration throughout the city continues.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Liverpool Waters, a mixed-use development in the city's disused northern docklands, has been identified as one of the largest megaprojects in the UK's history.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Everton's new stadium at Bramley-Moore Dock was regarded as the largest single-site private sector development in the United Kingdom at the time of construction.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Major events, business and political conferences regularly take place in the city and form an important part of the economy.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] In June 2014, Prime Minister David Cameron launched the International Festival for Business in Liverpool, the world's largest business event in 2014, and the largest in the UK since the Festival of Britain in 1951.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The Labour Party has chosen Liverpool numerous times since the mid-2010s for their annual Labour Party Conference.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Liverpool hosted the Eurovision Song Contest 2023.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Liverpool has been a centre of invention and innovation.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Railways, transatlantic steamships, municipal trams, and electric trains were all pioneered in Liverpool as modes of mass transit.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] In 1829 and 1836, the first railway tunnels in the world were constructed under Liverpool (Wapping Tunnel).
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] From 1950 to 1951, the world's first scheduled passenger helicopter service ran between Liverpool and Cardiff.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The first School for the Blind, Mechanics' Institute, High School for Girls, council house, and Juvenile Court were all founded in Liverpool.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Charities such as the RSPCA, NSPCC, Age Concern, Relate, and Citizen's Advice Bureau all evolved from work in the city.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The first British Nobel Prize was awarded in 1902 to Ronald Ross, professor at the School of Tropical Medicine, the first school of its kind in the world.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Orthopaedic surgery was pioneered in Liverpool by Hugh Owen Thomas, and modern medical anaesthetics by Thomas Cecil Gray.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The world's first integrated sewer system was constructed in Liverpool by James Newlands, appointed in 1847 as the UK's first borough engineer.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Liverpool also founded the UK's first Underwriters' Association and the first Institute of Accountants.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The Western world's first financial derivatives (cotton futures) were traded on the Liverpool Cotton Exchange in the late 1700s.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] In the arts, Liverpool was home to the first lending library (The Lyceum), athenaeum society (Liverpool Athenaeum), arts centre (Bluecoat Chambers), and public art conservation centre (National Conservation Centre).
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] It is also home to the UK's oldest surviving classical orchestra (Royal Liverpool Philharmonic Orchestra) and repertory theatre (Liverpool Playhouse).
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] In 1864, Peter Ellis built the world's first iron-framed, curtain-walled office building, Oriel Chambers, which has become a defining feature of skyscrapers around the world.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The UK's first purpose-built department store was Compton House, completed in 1867 for the retailer J.R.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] It was the largest store in the world at the time.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Between 1862 and 1867, Liverpool held an annual Grand Olympic Festival.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Devised by John Hulley and Charles Pierre Melly, these games were the first to be wholly amateur in nature and international in outlook.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The programme of the first modern Olympiad in Athens in 1896 was almost identical to that of the Liverpool Olympics.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] In 1865, Hulley co-founded the National Olympian Association in Liverpool, a forerunner of the British Olympic Association.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Its articles of foundation provided the framework for the Olympic Charter.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] A concept devised by retail entrepreneur David Lewis, the first Christmas grotto opened in Lewis's department store in Liverpool in 1879.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Sir Alfred Lewis Jones, a shipowner, introduced bananas to the UK via Liverpool's docks in 1884.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The Mersey Railway, opened in 1886, incorporated the world's first tunnel under a tidal estuary and the world's first deep-level underground stations (Liverpool James Street railway station).
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] In 1889, borough engineer John Alexander Brodie invented the football goal net.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] He was also a pioneer in the use of pre-fabricated housing and oversaw the construction of the UK's first ring road (A5058) and intercity highway (East Lancashire Road), as well as the Queensway Tunnel linking Liverpool and Birkenhead.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Described as "the eighth wonder of the world" at the time of its construction, it was the longest underwater tunnel in the world for 24 years.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] In 1897, the Lumière brothers filmed Liverpool, including what is believed to be the world's first tracking shot, taken from the Liverpool Overhead Railway, the world's first elevated electrified railway.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The Overhead Railway was the first railway in the world to use electric multiple units, employ automatic signalling, and install an escalator.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Liverpool inventor Frank Hornby was a visionary in toy development and manufacture, producing three of the most popular lines of toys in the 20th century: Meccano, Hornby Model Railways (both in 1901), and Dinky Toys in 1934.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The British Interplanetary Society, founded in Liverpool in 1933 by Phillip Ellaby Cleator, is the world's oldest existing organisation devoted to the promotion of spaceflight.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Its journal, the *Journal of the British Interplanetary Society*, is the longest-running astronautical publication in the world.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] In 1999, Liverpool was the first city outside London to be awarded blue plaques by English Heritage in recognition of the "significant contribution made by its sons and daughters in all walks of life".
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] For the purposes of local government, Liverpool is classified as a metropolitan borough with city status.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The metropolitan borough is located within both the county of Merseyside and the Liverpool City Region.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Each of these geographical areas is treated as an administrative area with different levels of local governance applying to each.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Liverpool City Council is the governing body solely for the Metropolitan Borough of Liverpool and performs functions that are standard of an English Unitary Authority.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The Liverpool City Region Combined Authority and the Mayor of the Liverpool City Region reserve major strategic powers over such things as transport, economic development and regeneration for the city along with the 5 surrounding boroughs of the Liverpool City Region.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The Combined Authority has competency over areas which have been devolved by national government and are specific to the city region.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Nevertheless, there are a few exceptions to local governance apart from these two structures.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Liverpool was administered by Merseyside County Council between 1974 and 1986 and some residual aspects of organisation which date back to this time have survived.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] When the County Council was disbanded in 1986, most civic functions were transferred to Liverpool City Council.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] However, several authorities such as the police and fire and rescue service, continue to be run at a county-wide level.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The county of Merseyside, therefore, continues to exist as an administrative area for a few limited services only, while the capability and capacity of the Liverpool City Region Combined Authority is evolving over time.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The city also elects five members of Parliament (MPs) to the Westminster Parliament, all Labour as of the 2024 general election.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Liverpool City Council operates under a constitution comprising 85 city councillors who are directly elected by the Liverpool electorate every four years and represent a variety of different political parties.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The city councillors make decisions about local services for the city's people.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] At each election, the political party that wins the majority of the 85 council seats leads the council for the following four years.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The local leader of this party assumes the role of Leader of the City Council who then chairs a Cabinet of 9 councillors who are assigned specific responsibilities known as 'portfolios'.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The City Council's decisions and scrutiny of activities are undertaken by a number of different committees and panels which include the Overview and Scrutiny Committees, Scrutiny Panels, Regulatory Committees and other committees.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The day-to-day management of the council is carried out by the management team which includes the Chief Executive and several directors and senior officers.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The management team works with the Cabinet and councillors to deliver strategic direction and priorities such as the budget and the City Plan.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Every four years, the city elects 85 councillors from 64 local council wards.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] During the 2023 Liverpool City Council election, the Labour Party consolidated its control of Liverpool City Council, following on from the previous elections.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The Conservative Party, the political party in power at national government, had no representation on Liverpool City Council.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Only 27.27% of the eligible Liverpool electorate turned out to vote.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Throughout most of the 19th and early 20th centuries, Liverpool was a municipal stronghold of Toryism.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] However, support for the Conservative Party in recent times has been among the lowest in any part of Britain, particularly since the monetarist economic policies of former prime minister Margaret Thatcher.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] After the 1979 general election, many have claimed that her victory contributed to longstanding high unemployment and decline in the city.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Liverpool is one of the Labour Party's key strongholds; however, the city has also seen hard times under Labour governments.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] In recent years, Liverpool City Council began an extensive improvement program designed to ensure that the authority makes efficient use of taxpayers' money and to encourage more business and investment in the city.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Grosvenor Group, the property company responsible for Liverpool One, commended the changes as an "opportunity for bold thinking in liverpool".
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] In 2021, a highly critical government inspection and subsequent report of Liverpool City Council (referred to as the Caller report) identified multiple shortcomings at Liverpool City Council.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, Robert Jenrick sent government commissioners to oversee the City Council's highways, regeneration, property management, governance and financial decision-making.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The authority was compelled to commit to a three-year improvement plan in which the entire structure of the council would be overhauled.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] As a result of the intervention, major structural changes at the City Council took place by the 2023 United Kingdom local elections, which were labelled "the most unpredictable [elections] in the city's history".
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The number of electoral wards in the city was doubled from 30 to 64, while the overall number of city councillors up for election was reduced from 90 to 85.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] In future, the council would also change to 'all out' elections every four years whereby every single city councillor would be eligible for re-election at the same time.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The role of elected city mayor was also abolished and the Council reverted to the previous Leader and Cabinet style of leadership.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The outcome of the elections were seen not only as a test of how the general public would respond to the government intervention in the city, but also to Prime Minister Rishi Sunak's government as a whole.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Liam Robinson became the new Leader of Liverpool City Council at the 2023 City Council election.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The Liverpool Strategic Futures Advisory Panel, chaired by the Mayor of Liverpool City Region Steve Rotheram, and including several high-profile figures with experience in local government, was established.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The panel was tasked with directing the council's long-term future outside of government intervention measures and to advise on plans and priorities that the city should pursue.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] In February 2008, Liverpool City Council was reported to be the worst-performing council in the country, receiving just a one-star rating (classified as inadequate).
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The main cause of the poor rating was attributed to the council's poor handling of tax-payer money, including the accumulation of a £20 million shortfall while the city held the title of European Capital of Culture.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] In April 2024, the Office for Local Government released a ranking of local authorities, placing Liverpool City Council 317th out of a possible 318.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The Lord Mayor of Liverpool is an ancient ceremonial role.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Councillors within Liverpool City Council (not the general public) elect the Lord Mayor annually, who then serves a one-year term.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The Lord Mayor is also the presiding officer for Liverpool City Council full meetings.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Liverpool is one of the six constituent boroughs of the Liverpool City Region.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The Mayor of the Liverpool City Region is directly every four years by residents of those six boroughs and oversees the Liverpool City Region Combined Authority.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The Combined Authority is the top-tier administrative body for the local governance of the city region and is tasked with taking major strategic decisions on issues such as transport and investment, economic development, employment and skills, tourism, culture, housing and physical infrastructure.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Liverpool is included within five parliamentary constituencies, through which MPs are elected to represent the city in Westminster: Liverpool Garston, Liverpool Riverside, Liverpool Walton, Liverpool Wavertree and Liverpool West Derby.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] At the last general election, all were won by Labour with representation being from Maria Eagle, Kim Johnson, Dan Carden, Paula Barker and Ian Byrne respectively.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Liverpool has been described as having "the most splendid setting of any English city".
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The Mersey Estuary separates Liverpool from the Wirral Peninsula.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The boundaries of Liverpool are adjacent to Bootle, Crosby and Maghull in south Sefton to the north, and Kirkby, Huyton, Prescot and Halewood in Knowsley to the east.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Liverpool experiences a temperate maritime climate (Köppen: *Cfb*), like much of the British Isles, with relatively mild summers, cool winters and rainfall spread fairly evenly throughout the year.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Rainfall and temperature records had been kept at Bidston Hill since 1867, but records for atmospheric pressure go back as far as at least 1846.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Bidston closed down in 2002 but the Met Office also has a weather station at Crosby.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Since records began in 1867, temperatures have ranged from −17.6 °C (0.3 °F) on 21 December 2010 to 34.5 °C (94.1 °F) on 2 August 1990, although Liverpool Airport recorded a temperature of 35.0 °C (95.0 °F) on 19 July 2006.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The lowest amount of sunshine on record was 16.5 hours in December 1927 whereas the most was 314.5 hours in July 2013.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Tornado activity or funnel cloud formation is very rare in and around the Liverpool area and tornadoes that do form are usually weak.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Recent tornadoes or funnel clouds in Merseyside have been seen in 1998 and 2014.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] During the period 1981–2010, Crosby recorded an average of 32.8 days of air frost per year, which is low for the United Kingdom.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Snow is fairly common during the winter although heavy snow is rare.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Snow generally falls between November and March but can occasionally fall earlier and later.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] In recent times, the earliest snowfall was on 1 October 2008 while the latest occurred on 15 May 2012.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Although historically, the earliest snowfall occurred on 10 September 1908 and the latest on 2 June 1975.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Rainfall, although light, is quite a common occurrence in Liverpool, with the wettest month on record being August 1956, which recorded 221.2 mm (8.71 in) of rain and the driest being February 1932, with 0.9 mm (0.035 in).
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Weather station is located 7 miles (11 km) from the Liverpool city centre.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Sunshine hours were recorded at the Bidston Observatory from the period of 1971–2000.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Humidity was recorded at the Bidston Observatory for the period of 1975–June 2002.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The period Jul–Sep 1992 has no record, with Jan–May 2001 reporting unreliabe data.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] From 1867–2002, extremes were recorded at the Bidston Observatory in Wirral.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Since 1983, extremes were recorded at Crosby, Sefton.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] In 2010, Liverpool City Council and the Primary Care Trust commissioned the Mersey Forest to complete "A Green Infrastructure Strategy" for the city.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] This is achieved by restricting inappropriate development within the designated areas and imposing stricter conditions on permitted building.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The green belt was first drawn up in 1983 under Merseyside County Council and the size in the city amounts to 530 hectares (5.3 km2; 2.0 mi2).
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Since the mid-20th century, Scouser has become the predominant demonym for the inhabitants of Liverpool, and is strongly associated with the Scouse accent and dialect of the city.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The Scouse accent is described as progressively diverging from the Lancastrian accent in the late 19th century.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] The etymology of Scouser is derived from the traditional dish Scouse brought to the area by sailors travelling through Liverpool's port.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Professor Tony Crowley writes that up until the 1950s, inhabitants of Liverpool were generally referred to by a number of demonyms, including, in the mid-20th century, the rival terms of 'Liverpolitan' and 'Liverpudlian'.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Debate surrounded the lexicology of these terms and their connotations of social class.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Professor John Belchem suggests that a series of other nicknames such as 'Dick Liver', 'Dicky Sam' and 'whacker' were used, but gradually fell out of use.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] Belchem and Philip Boland suggest that comedic radio presenters and entertainers brought the Liverpool identity to a national audience, which in turn encouraged locals to be gradually more known as 'scousers'.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p01] By the time that Frank Shaw's *My Liverpool, a Celebration of 'Scousetown'* was published in 1971, Belchem argues, 'Scouser' had firmly become the dominant demonym.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The city of Liverpool is at the core of a much larger and more populous metropolitan area; however, at the most recent UK Census in 2021, the area governed by Liverpool City Council had a population of 486,100, a 4.2% increase from the previous Census in 2011.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] This figure increased to 500,500 people by 2022, according to data from Liverpool City Council.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Taking in to account how local government is organised within the cities and metropolitan areas of England, the Liverpool was the fifth largest of England's 'core cities' and had the second-overall-highest population density of those, by 2021.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The population of the city has steadily risen since the 2001 Census.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] As well as having a growing population, the population density also grew at the 2021 Census compared to the previous census.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Since 2011, its population size ranked 10th out of 309 local authority areas.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The population of the city is comparatively younger than that of England as a whole.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Family life in the city is also growing at odds with the North West England region as a whole: At the 2021 Census, the percentage of households including a couple without children increased in Liverpool, but fell across the North West.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The percentage of people aged 16 years and over (excluding full-time students) who were employed also increased in Liverpool compared to the overall North West region where it fell.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The 2021 Census also showed that Liverpool's ethnic and international population was growing.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The number of residents in the city born outside of England has increased since the previous census, while the number of residents who did not identify with any national identity associated with the UK has also increased at a faster rate than England as a whole.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The overall share of the city's population who identified as Asian and Black increased, while the percentage who identified as white decreased in the city compared with previous Census.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] It has been argued that the city can claim to have one of the strongest Irish heritages in the United Kingdom, with as many as 75 per cent (estimated) of Liverpool's population with some form of Irish ancestry.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The growing population of Liverpool in the 21st century reverses a trend which took place between the 1930s and 2001, when the population of the city proper effectively halved.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] At the 1931 United Kingdom census, Liverpool's population reached an all-time high of 846,302.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Following this peak, in response to central government policy, the Council authority of Liverpool then built and owned large several 'new town' council estates in the suburbs within Liverpool's metropolitan area.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Tens of thousands of people were systematically relocated to new housing in areas such as Halton, Knowsley, St Helens, Sefton, Wirral, Cheshire West and Chester, West Lancashire, Warrington and as far as North Wales.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Liverpool is typically grouped with the wider Merseyside (plus Halton) area for the purpose of defining its metropolitan footprint, and there are several methodologies.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Sometimes, this metropolitan area is broadened to encompass urban settlements in the neighbouring counties of Lancashire and Cheshire.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The Office for National Statistics in the United Kingdom uses the international standardised International Territorial Levels (ITLs) to divide up the economic territory of the UK.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] This enables the ONS to calculate regional and local statistics and data.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The ONS uses a series of codes to identify these areas.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] North West England (code TLD) At the 2021 Census, the ITL 1 region of North West England had a usual resident population of 7,417,300.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Merseyside (code TLD7) The ITL 2 region of Merseyside is defined as the area comprising East Merseyside (TLD71) plus Liverpool (TLD72), Sefton (TLD73) and Wirral (TLD74).
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Therefore, the total population of the ITL 2 Merseyside region was 1,551,500 based on the 2021 Census.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The smallest ITL 3 area classed as Liverpool (code TLD72), therefore, had a population of 486,100 at the 2021 Census.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] At the 2021 Census, the ONS used a refreshed concept of built-up areas (BUAs) based on the physical built environment, using satellite imagery to recognise developed land, such as cities, towns and villages.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] This allows the ONS to investigate economic and social statistics based on actual settlements where most people live.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Data from the 2021 Census is not directly comparable with 2011 Census data due to this revised methodology.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Using the population figures of BUAs at the 2021 Census (excluding London), Liverpool Built-up Area is the third largest in England with some 506,565 usual residents (behind only Birmingham and Leeds).
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Liverpool's built-up area is, therefore, larger than the major English cities of Bristol, Manchester, Newcastle upon Tyne, Nottingham and Sheffield.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Excluding London, the Liverpool City Region was the fourth-largest combined authority area in England, by 2021.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The population is approximately 1.6 million.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The Liverpool City Region is a political and economic partnership between local authorities including Liverpool, plus the Metropolitan boroughs of Knowsley, Sefton, St Helens, Wirral and the Borough of Halton.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The Liverpool City Region Combined Authority exercises strategic governance powers for the region in many areas.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The economic data of the Liverpool city region is of particular policy interest to the Office for National Statistics, particularly as the British Government continuously explores the potential to negotiate increased devolved powers for each combined authority area.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] In 2006, in an attempt to harmonise the series of metropolitan areas across the European Union, ESPON (now European Observation Network for Territorial Development and Cohesion) released a study defining a "Liverpool/Birkenhead Metropolitan area" with an estimated population of 2.241 million people.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The metro area comprised a functional urban area consisting of a contiguous urban sprawl, labour pool, and commuter Travel to work areas.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The analysis defined this metropolitan area as Liverpool itself, combined with the surrounding areas of Birkenhead, Wigan/Ashton, Warrington, Widnes/Runcorn, Chester, Southport, Ellesmere Port, Ormskirk and Skelmersdale.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Liverpool and Manchester are sometimes considered as one large polynuclear metropolitan area, or megalopolis.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] In recent decades, Liverpool's population is becoming more multicultural.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] According to the 2021 census, 77% of all Liverpool residents described their ethnic group as White English, Welsh, Scottish, Northern Irish or British.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The remaining 23% were described as non-White English/British.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Between 2011 and 2021, there was population growth across all ethnic groups, except 'White English/British' and 'Any Other', where there were overall losses.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The number of 'Other White residents' in Liverpool also increased by almost 12,000 people, with notable increases in the 'Other Asian', 'Arab', and 'Other Mixed/Multiple' population categories.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The non-White English/British population as a percentage of the total population across the 'newly organised city electoral wards' ranged from 5% in the Orrell Park ward to 69% in the Princes Park ward.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Nine out of ten Liverpool residents regarded English as their main language.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The most spoken non-English languages in the city were Arabic (5,743 main speakers) followed by Polish (4,809 main speakers).
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Overall, almost 45,000 residents had a main language that was not English.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Liverpool is home to the UK's oldest black community, dating back to at least the 1730s.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Some Liverpudlians can trace their black ancestry in the city back ten generations.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Early Black settlers in the city included seamen, the children of traders sent to be educated, and freed slaves, since slaves entering the country after 1722 were deemed free men.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Since the 20th century, Liverpool is also noted for its large African-Caribbean, Ghanaian, and Somali communities, formed of more recent African-descended immigrants and their subsequent generations.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The city is also home to the oldest Chinese community in Europe; the first residents of the city's Chinatown arrived as seamen in the 19th century.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The traditional Chinese gateway erected in Liverpool's Chinatown is the largest such gateway outside China.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Liverpool also has a long-standing Filipino community.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Lita Roza, a singer from Liverpool who was the first woman to achieve a UK number one hit, had Filipino ancestry.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The city is also known for its large Irish and Welsh populations.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] During, and in the decades following, the Great Irish Famine in the mid-19th century, up to two million Irish people travelled to Liverpool within one decade, with many subsequently departing for the United States.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] By 1851, more than 20 per cent of the population of Liverpool was Irish.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] At the 2001 Census, 1.17 per cent of the population were Welsh-born and 0.75 per cent were born in the Republic of Ireland, while 0.54 per cent were born in Northern Ireland, but many more Liverpudlians are of legacy Welsh or Irish ancestry.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Other contemporary ethnicities include Indian, Latin American, Malaysian, and Yemeni communities, which number several thousand each.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The thousands of migrants and sailors passing through Liverpool resulted in a religious diversity that is still apparent today.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] This is reflected in the equally diverse collection of religious buildings, including two Christian cathedrals.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Liverpool is known to be England's 'most Catholic city', with a Catholic population much larger than in other parts of England.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] This is mainly due to high historic Irish migration to the city and their descendants since.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The parish church of Liverpool is the Anglican Our Lady and St Nicholas, colloquially known as "the sailors church", which has existed near the waterfront since 1257.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] It regularly plays host to Catholic masses.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Other notable churches include the Greek Orthodox Church of St Nicholas (built in the Neo-Byzantine architecture style) and the Gustav Adolf Church (the Swedish Seamen's Church, reminiscent of Nordic styles).
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Liverpool's wealth as a port city enabled the construction of two enormous cathedrals in the 20th century.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The Anglican Cathedral, which was designed by Sir Giles Gilbert Scott and plays host to the annual Liverpool Shakespeare Festival, has one of the longest naves, largest organs and heaviest and highest peals of bells in the world.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The Roman Catholic Metropolitan Cathedral, on Mount Pleasant next to Liverpool Science Park, was initially planned to be even larger.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Of Sir Edwin Lutyens's original design, only the crypt was completed.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The cathedral was eventually built to a simpler design by Sir Frederick Gibberd.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] While this is on a smaller scale than Lutyens' original design, it still incorporates the largest panel of stained glass in the world.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The road running between the two cathedrals is called Hope Street.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The cathedral has long been colloquially referred to as "Paddy's Wigwam" due to its shape.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Liverpool contains several synagogues, of which the Grade I listed Moorish Revival Princes Road Synagogue is architecturally the most notable.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Princes Road is widely considered to be the most magnificent of Britain's Moorish Revival synagogues and one of the finest buildings in Liverpool.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Liverpool has a thriving Jewish community with a further two orthodox Synagogues, one in the Allerton district of the city and a second in the Childwall district of the city where a significant Jewish community reside.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] A third orthodox Synagogue in the Greenbank Park area of L17 has recently closed and is a listed 1930s structure.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] There is also a Lubavitch Chabad House and a reform synagogue.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Liverpool has had a Jewish community since the mid-18th century.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The Jewish population of Liverpool is around 5,000.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The Liverpool Talmudical College existed from 1914 until 1990, when its classes moved to the Childwall Synagogue.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Liverpool also has a Hindu community, with a Mandir on Edge Lane, Edge Hill.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The Shri Radha Krishna Temple from the Hindu Cultural Organisation in Liverpool is located there.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Liverpool also has the Guru Nanak Sikh Gurdwara in Wavertree and a Baháʼí Centre in the same area.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The city had the earliest Mosque in England and possibly the UK, founded in 1887 by William Abdullah Quilliam, a lawyer who had converted to Islam who set up the Liverpool Muslim Institute in a terraced house on West Derby Road.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Apart from the first mosque in England which now houses a museum, the largest and main one, Al-Rahma mosque, was also the third purpose-built mosque in the United Kingdom.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The second largest mosque in Liverpool is the Masjid Al-Taiseer.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Other mosques in the city include the Bait ul Lateef Ahmadiyya Mosque, Hamza Center (Community Center), Islamic community centre, Liverpool Mosque and Islamic Institute, Liverpool Towhid Centre, Masjid Annour, and the Shah Jalal Mosque.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Liverpool forms an integral part of North West England's economy, the third largest regional economy in the United Kingdom.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The city is also a major contributor to the economy of Liverpool City Region, worth over £40 billion per year.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The local authority area governed by Liverpool City Council accounts for 39% of the Liverpool city region's total jobs, 40% of its total GVA and 35% of its total businesses.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] At the local authority level, the city's GVA (balanced) at current basic prices was £14.3 billion in 2021.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Its GDP at current market prices was £15.9 billion.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] This equates to £32,841 per head of the population.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] At the 2021 United Kingdom census, 51.1% of Liverpool's population aged 16 years and over was classed as employed, 44.2% economically inactive and 4.8% unemployed.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] According to the ONS Business Register and Employment Survey 2021, some industries within Liverpool perform strongly compared to other local authorities in Great Britain.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Liverpool features in the national top 20 for number of jobs in education; construction; wholesale and retail trade; repair of motor vehicles and motorcycles; transportation and storage; financial and insurance activities and professional, scientific and technical activities.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] In 2023, Liverpool City Council set out an economic growth plan for the city over the following 20 years.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The City Council will have particular focus on economic sectors such as the visitor economy (tourism), culture, life sciences, digital and creative sectors, and advanced car manufacturing.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] According to the International passenger Survey, from the ONS, Liverpool was one of the top 5 most visited cities in the UK by overseas tourists in 2022.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] As of the same year, the city's tourist industry was worth a total of £3.5 billion annually and was part of a larger city region tourist industry worth £5 billion.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] A consistent calendar of major events, as well as a plethora of cultural attractions, continue to provide a significant draw for tourists.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Tourism related to the Beatles is worth an estimated £100 million to the Liverpool economy each year alone.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Liverpool One, as well as a growing retail offer overall, has led to the city being one of the most prominent destinations for shopping in the UK.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Liverpool Cruise Terminal, which is situated close to the Pier Head, enables tourists to berth in the centre of the city.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Liverpool is home to the Knowledge Quarter, a 450-acre city centre district that hosts some of the world's most influential institutions in science, health, technology, education, music and the creative performing arts.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The UK government has also identified the city as a 'pharmaceutical production superpower' and one of the UK's leading regions for bioprocessing.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The accolade led to the government choosing the city for England's second ever 'Investment Zone' in 2023.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] This will involve millions of pounds being invested over the coming years in to science orientated districts including the Knowledge Quarter and the so-called 'pharma cluster' in the city suburb of Speke.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The two clusters form an internationally significant role in infectious disease control.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Liverpool City Council also plan to invest in the city's Baltic Triangle, which is renowned in the creative and digital industries.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Car manufacturing also takes place in the city at the Jaguar Land Rover Halewood plant, where the Range Rover Evoque model is assembled.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] In 2023, Jaguar Land Rover announced that the Halewood plant would begin to shift its focus to electric car production.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Historically, the economy of Liverpool was centred on the city's port and manufacturing base.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Today, the Port of Liverpool is the UK's fourth-largest port by tonnage of freight, handling over 30 million tonnes in 2020.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The city is also the UK's largest port for transatlantic trade, handling 45% of the country's trade from the United States.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] In 2023, the city was chosen by the British government to be a designated Freeport to encourage growing international commerce.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The Liverpool2 container terminal, completed in 2022, has greatly increased the volume of cargo which Liverpool is able to handle and has facilitated the world's biggest container vessels.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Liverpool's rich architectural base has helped the city become the second most filmed city in the UK outside London.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] As well as being a featured location in its own right, it often doubles up for Chicago, London, Moscow, New York City, Paris and Rome.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The Depot studios, close to the city centre, provide space for film and TV productions.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Major economic projects planned for the city include the revitalisation of disused land in the North docks/Ten Streets area, Liverpool Waters and a new purpose-built TV studio at the former Littlewoods Pools building, adjacent to the Depot.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The policy agenda of the British Government is to continuously monitor the economy and productivity of the UK's core cities within the context of their respective city regions.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The government's longer-term plan is to assess each area's potential for increased devolution and transfer of additional powers and budgets from central government in Whitehall to their corresponding combined authorities.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] As such, official statistics about Liverpool's economy within the context of the Liverpool City Region, are closely monitored by the Office for National Statistics.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] This allows policy and decision makers to more accurately assess the 'functional economic area' of the city, which is not bound by traditional local government geographies.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] As of 2023, there are ten city regions in England with combined authorities.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Liverpool's long commercial history has given rise to a considerable variety of architectural styles found within the city, ranging from 16th-century Tudor buildings to modern-day contemporary architecture.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The majority of buildings in the city date from the late 18th century onwards, the period during which the city grew into one of the foremost powers in the British Empire.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] There are over 2,500 listed buildings in Liverpool, of which 27 are Grade I listed and 85 are Grade II* listed.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The city also has a greater number of public sculptures than any other location in the United Kingdom aside from Westminster and significant number of Georgian houses still exist.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] This richness of architecture has subsequently seen Liverpool described by English Heritage, as England's finest Victorian city.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The value of Liverpool's architecture and design was recognised in 2004, when several areas throughout the city were declared a UNESCO World Heritage Site.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Known as the Liverpool Maritime Mercantile City, the sites were added in recognition of the city's role in the development of international trade and docking technology.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] However, this status was revoked in July 2021, when UNESCO resolved that recent and proposed developments, such as the Bramley-Moore Dock Stadium and Liverpool Waters projects, had resulted in the "serious deterioration" of the area's significance.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] As a major British port, the docks in Liverpool have historically been central to the city's development.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Several major docking firsts have occurred in the city including the construction of the world's first enclosed wet dock (the Old Dock) in 1715 and the first ever hydraulic lifting cranes.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The best-known dock in Liverpool is the Royal Albert Dock, which was constructed in 1846 and today comprises the largest single collection of Grade I listed buildings anywhere in Britain.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Built under the guidance of Jesse Hartley, it was considered to be one of the most advanced docks anywhere in the world upon completion and is often attributed with helping the city to become one of the most important ports in the world.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Today, the Royal Albert Dock houses restaurants, bars, shops, two hotels as well as the Merseyside Maritime Museum, International Slavery Museum, Tate Liverpool and The Beatles Story.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] North of the city centre is Stanley Dock, home to the Stanley Dock Tobacco Warehouse, which was at the time of its construction in 1901, the world's largest building in terms of area and today stands as the world's largest brick-work building.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] One of the most famous locations in Liverpool is the Pier Head, renowned for the trio of buildings—the Royal Liver Building, the Cunard Building and the Port of Liverpool Building—which sit upon it.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Collectively referred to as the *Three Graces*, these buildings stand as a testament to the great wealth in the city during the late 19th and early 20th centuries.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Built in a variety of architectural styles, they are recognised as being the symbol of 'maritime Liverpool' and are regarded by many as contributing to one of the most impressive waterfronts in the world.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] In the 21st century, several areas along Liverpool's waterfront have undergone significant redevelopment.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Among the notable developments are the Museum of Liverpool, the construction of the Liverpool Arena, ACC Liverpool and Exhibition Centre Liverpool on King's Dock, Alexandra Tower and 1 Princes Dock on Prince's Dock and Liverpool Marina around Coburg and Brunswick Docks.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The Wheel of Liverpool opened on 25 March 2010.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] However, plans to redevelop parts of Liverpool city centre have been marred by controversy.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] In December 2016, a newly formed company called North Point Global Ltd. was given the rights to develop part of the docks under the "New Chinatown" working name.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Though heavily advertised in Liverpool, Hong Kong and Chinese cities with high-profile advertisements and videos, the "New Chinatown" development failed to materialise.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] In January 2018, the *Liverpool Echo* and *Asia Times* revealed that the site remained sans any construction.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] North Point Global as well as its subcontractor "Bilt" had both declared bankruptcy, and the small investors (mostly middle class couples) who had already paid money for the apartments had lost most of their savings in them.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Liverpool's historic position as one of the most important trading ports in the world has meant that over time many grand buildings have been constructed in the city as headquarters for shipping firms, insurance companies, banks and other large firms.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The great wealth this brought then allowed for the development of grand civic buildings, which were designed to allow the local administrators to 'run the city with pride'.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The commercial district is centred on the Castle Street, Dale Street and Old Hall Street areas of the city, with many of the area's roads still following their medieval layout.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Having developed predominantly over a period of three centuries, the area is regarded as one of the most important architectural locations in the city, as recognised by its inclusion in Liverpool's former World Heritage site.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The oldest building in the area is the Grade I listed Liverpool Town Hall, which is located at the top of Castle Street and dates from 1754.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Often regarded as the city's finest piece of Georgian architecture, the building is known as one of the most extravagantly decorated civic buildings anywhere in Britain.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Also on Castle Street is the Grade I listed Bank of England Building, constructed between 1845 and 1848, as one of only three provincial branches of the national bank.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Among the other buildings in the area are the Tower Buildings, Albion House (the former White Star Line headquarters), the Municipal Buildings and Oriel Chambers, which is considered to be one of the earliest Modernist style buildings ever built.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The area around William Brown Street is referred to as the city's 'Cultural Quarter', owing to the presence of numerous civic buildings, including the William Brown Library, Walker Art Gallery, Picton Reading Rooms and World Museum Liverpool.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The area is dominated by neo-classical architecture, of which the most prominent, St George's Hall, is widely regarded as the best example of a neo-classical building anywhere in Europe.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] A Grade I listed building, it was constructed between 1840 and 1855 to serve a variety of civic functions in the city and its doors are inscribed with "S.P.Q.L." (Latin *senatus populusque Liverpudliensis*), meaning "the senate and people of Liverpool".
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] William Brown Street is also home to numerous public monuments and sculptures, including Wellington's Column and the Steble Fountain.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Many others are located around the area, particularly in St John's Gardens, which was specifically developed for this purpose.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The William Brown Street area has been likened to a modern recreation of the Roman Forum.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] While the majority of Liverpool's architecture dates from the mid-18th century onwards, there are several buildings that pre-date this time.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] One of the oldest surviving buildings is Speke Hall, a Tudor manor house located in the south of the city, which was completed in 1598.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The building is one of the few remaining timber framed Tudor houses left in the north of England and is particularly noted for its Victorian interiors, which were added in the mid-19th century.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] In addition to Speke Hall, many of the city's other oldest surviving buildings are also former manor houses including Croxteth Hall and Woolton Hall, which were completed in 1702 and 1704 respectively.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The oldest building within the city centre is the Grade I listed Bluecoat Chambers, which was built between 1717 and 1718.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Constructed in British Queen Anne style architecture, the building was influenced in part by the work of Christopher Wren and was originally the home of the Bluecoat School (who later moved to a larger site in Wavertree in the south of the city).
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Since 1908, it has acted as a centre for arts in Liverpool.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Liverpool is noted for having two cathedrals, each of which imposes over the landscape around it.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The Anglican Cathedral, which was constructed between 1904 and 1978, is the largest cathedral in Britain and the fifth largest in the world.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Designed and built in Gothic style, it is regarded as one of the greatest buildings to have been constructed during the 20th century and was described by former British Poet Laureate, John Betjeman, as "one of the great buildings of the world".
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The Roman Catholic Metropolitan Cathedral was constructed between 1962 and 1967 and is known as one of the first cathedrals to break the traditional longitudinal design.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] In the 21st century, many parts of Liverpool's city centre have undergone significant redevelopment and regeneration after years of decline.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] So far, the largest of these developments has been Liverpool One, which saw almost £1 billion invested in the redevelopment of 42 acres (17 hectares) of land, providing new retail, commercial, residential and leisure space.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Around the north of the city centre, several new skyscrapers have also been constructed including the RIBA award-winning Unity Buildings and West Tower, which at 140m is Liverpool's tallest building.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Many redevelopment schemes are also in progress including Circus, King's Dock, Paddington Village and Liverpool Waters.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] The Register of Historic Parks and Gardens of Special Historic Interest in England describes Merseyside's Victorian Parks as collectively the "most important in the country".
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p02] Liverpool has ten listed parks and cemeteries, including two Grade I and five Grade II*, more than any other English city apart from London.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Liverpool has an extensive transport infrastructure that connects the city with its metropolitan area, the rest of the United Kingdom, Europe and the world.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Various modes of transport provide considerable connections by road, rail, air and sea.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The local network of buses, trains and ferries is managed by Merseytravel, on behalf of the Liverpool City Region Combined Authority and the Metro Mayor of the Liverpool City Region.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The Mayor and Combined Authority have control of a devolved transport budget and associated transport powers for this local system.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The city's major port and international airport provide global links for both passengers and freight.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The city sits at the centre of a much larger metropolitan area.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Its suburbs run contiguously into the neighbouring boroughs defined by the ONS as the Liverpool Built-up Area.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The wider City Region and Merseyside in general is densely urbanised and divided by several motorways and major roads.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The city is served by a network motorways.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The three motorways in closest proximity are the M58 to the north, and M62 and M57 to the east.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] To the north, the M58 motorway runs 12 miles and provides links to the neighbouring counties of Lancashire and Greater Manchester, finally joining with the M6 west of Wigan.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] To the east, the M62 runs across the north of England, ultimately connecting Liverpool with Hull on the opposite coast, and along the route with several large cities including Manchester, Leeds and Bradford.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The M62 also provides a connection to both the M6 and M1 motorways, providing indirect links to more distant areas including Birmingham, London, Nottingham, Preston and Sheffield.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] To the east, but running north–south, the M57 acts as a 10-mile ring road for the city itself and links the M62 and M58 motorways, as well as the A580 East Lancashire Road providing a link directly to the A5300 that links to the bridges that cross the Mersey to the south of the city.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] To the south, Liverpool is connected to Widnes and Warrington via the A562 and A5300 and across the River Mersey to Runcorn in Cheshire, via the Silver Jubilee and Mersey Gateway bridges.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The M56 motorway then provides routes into parts of the neighbouring counties, with connections to the Wirral and North Wales, and a direct route to Manchester Airport.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The Kingsway and Queensway Tunnels connect Liverpool with the settlements on the Wirral Peninsula across the Mersey to the west, including Birkenhead and Wallasey.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The A41 road and M53 motorway, which both begin in Birkenhead, link to Cheshire and Shropshire and via the A55, to North Wales.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The national network, which is managed by Network Rail, provides Liverpool with connections to major towns and cities across England.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The city's primary main line station is Liverpool Lime Street, which is the terminus for several lines into the city.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The station is served by six train operating companies: Avanti West Coast, East Midlands Railway, Northern Trains, Transport for Wales, TransPennine Express and West Midlands Trains.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Between them, the station is connected with direct services to numerous destinations including London Euston (in 2 hours 8 minutes with Pendolino trains), Birmingham New Street, Cleethorpes, Glasgow Central, Leeds, Manchester Piccadilly, Newcastle, Norwich, Nottingham, Preston, Sheffield and York.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Opened in 1836, Lime Street is the world's oldest main line terminus station still in use.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] In the south of the city, Liverpool South Parkway provides a connection to the city's airport.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The Port of Liverpool connects passengers and freight to Liverpool from all around the world.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Passenger ferry services depart from the city across the Irish Sea to Belfast and the Isle of Man.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Services are provided by several companies, including the Isle of Man Steam Packet Company, P&O Ferries and Stena Line.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The Liverpool Cruise Terminal handles over 200,000 passengers and crew annually and is located alongside the Pier Head in the city centre.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Berthing facilities for long-distance passenger cruises are provided and served by a large number of different cruise lines.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Ports in Australia, France, Faroe Islands, Iceland, North America, Norway, Spain and the Caribbean are served by the facility.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] As of 2022, the Port of Liverpool is the fourth busiest port in the UK by freight tonnage, handling 33 million tonnes of freight cargo.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] It is the main port in the country for transatlantic trade and the largest port on the west coast of the UK.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The Royal Seaforth and Liverpool2 container terminals are the port's two main terminals and handle a wide variety of cargo including containers, liquid and dry bulk cargoes such as coal and grain, biomass and roll-on/roll-off cargoes such as cars and trucks.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Leeds and Liverpool Canal runs into Liverpool city centre via Liverpool Canal Link at Pier Head since 2009.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Liverpool John Lennon Airport, which is located in the south of the city, provides direct air connections across the United Kingdom and Europe.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] It offers direct services to over 60 airports worldwide and to over 100 destinations via one-stop connections in Frankfurt, Dublin and Keflavík.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The airport is primarily served by low-cost airlines namely Aer Lingus, easyJet, Jet2.com, Loganair, Lufthansa, Ryanair, Widerøe and Wizz Air, although it does provide facilities for private aircraft.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Liverpool's urban railway network, known as Merseyrail, is one of the busiest and most extensive in the country.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The network provides approximately 30 million passenger journeys per year, across a system of 69 stations throughout Liverpool's metropolitan area, within the formal boundaries of the Liverpool city region and adjacent areas of Cheshire and Lancashire.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The network is predominantly electric and covers 75 miles (120 kilometres) of track.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Trains are owned and operated by the Merseyrail franchise and managed by Merseytravel under the direction of the Liverpool City Region Combined Authority.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Local services on the City Line are operated by Northern Trains, although the line itself remains part of the Merseyrail network.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Within Liverpool city centre, four stations and over 6+1⁄2 miles (10.5 kilometres) of tunnels are underground.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Birkenhead Hamilton Square and Liverpool James Street are the oldest deep level underground stations in the world.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] In 2023, for the first time in UK history, battery-powered passenger trains launched on Merseyrail tracks from the newly opened Headbolt Lane station in Kirkby.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Local bus services within and around Liverpool are managed by Merseytravel and are run by several different companies, including Arriva and Stagecoach Merseyside and South Lancashire.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The two principal termini for local buses are Queen Square bus station (located near Lime Street station) for services north and east of the city, and Liverpool One bus station (located near the Royal Albert Dock) for services to the south and east.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Cross-river services to the Wirral use roadside terminus points in Castle Street and Sir Thomas Street.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] A night bus service also operates on Saturdays providing services from the city centre across Liverpool and wider region.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Tour bus services are provided by Maghull Coaches which allow tourists to hop-on-hop-off and view historical landmarks and attractions, as well as Liverpool F.C. and Beatles related locations.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] National Express services operate from the Liverpool One bus station to and from destinations across the UK.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] In 2023, the Liverpool city region confirmed plans to become the second place outside London to implement bus franchising.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Local leaders have argued that it will improve services by transferring control over fares, ticketing and routes from bus companies to the Combined Authority.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The full implementation of bus franchising will take place by the end of 2028.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The cross-river ferry service in Liverpool, known as the Mersey Ferry, is managed and operated by Merseytravel, with services operating between the Pier Head in Liverpool city centre and both Woodside in Birkenhead and Seacombe in Wallasey.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Services operate at intervals ranging from 20 minutes, at peak times, to every hour during the middle of the day and at weekends.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] A scooter-sharing system and electric bicycle scheme operates throughout Liverpool which allows residents and visitors to move around the city on rented scooters and bicycles.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The scheme is operated by Swedish technology company Voi; riders are able to pick up and drop off bikes and scooters at various locations around the city.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] National Cycle Route 56, National Cycle Route 62 and National Cycle Route 810 run through Liverpool.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] As with other large cities, Liverpool is an important cultural centre within the United Kingdom, incorporating music, performing arts, museums and art galleries, literature and nightlife among others.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] In 2008, the cultural heritage of the city was celebrated with the city holding the title of European Capital of Culture, during which time a wide range of cultural celebrations took place in the city, including Go Superlambananas! and La Princesse.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Liverpool has also held Europe's largest music and poetry event, the Welsh national Eisteddfod, three times, despite being in England, in 1884, 1900, and 1929.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Liverpool is internationally known for music and is recognised by *Guinness World Records* as the "World Capital City of Pop".
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Musicians from the city have produced 58 No.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] 1 singles, more than any other city in the world.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Both the most successful male band and girl group in global music history have contained Liverpudlian members.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Liverpool is most famous as the birthplace of the Beatles and during the 1960s was at the forefront of the Beat Music movement, which would eventually lead to the British Invasion.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Many notable musicians of the time originated in the city including Billy J.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Kramer, Cilla Black, Gerry and the Pacemakers and the Searchers.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The influence of musicians from Liverpool, coupled with other cultural exploits of the time, such as the Liverpool poets, prompted American poet Allen Ginsberg to proclaim that the city was "the centre of consciousness of the human universe".
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Other musicians from Liverpool include Billy Fury, A Flock of Seagulls, Echo & the Bunnymen, Frankie Goes to Hollywood, Frankie Vaughan, Anathema, Ladytron, the Zutons, Cast, Atomic Kitten and Rebecca Ferguson.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The city is also home to the oldest surviving professional symphony orchestra in the UK, the Royal Liverpool Philharmonic Orchestra, which is based in the Philharmonic Hall.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The chief conductor of the orchestra is Vasily Petrenko.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Sir Edward Elgar dedicated his Pomp and Circumstance March No.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] 1 to the Liverpool Orchestral Society, and the piece had its first performance in the city in 1901.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Among Liverpool's curiosities, the Austrian émigré Fritz Spiegl is notable.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] He not only became a world expert on the etymology of Scouse, but composed the music to Z-cars and the Radio 4 UK Theme.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Well established festivals in the city include Africa Oyé and Brazilica which are the UK's largest free African and Brazilian music festivals respectively.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The dance music festival Creamfields was established by the Liverpool-based Cream clubbing brand which started life as a weekly event at Nation nightclub.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] There are numerous music venues located across the city, however, the Liverpool Arena is by far the largest.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Opened in 2008, the 11,000-seat arena hosted the MTV Europe Music Awards the same year, and since then has played host to world-renowned acts such as Andrea Bocelli, Beyoncé, Elton John, Kanye West, Kasabian, the Killers, Lady Gaga, Oasis, Pink, Rihanna, and UB40.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The contest was held at Liverpool Arena, and consisted of two semi-finals on 9 and 11 May and a final on 13 May 2023.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] This was the first time that the contest took place in the city, and was also a record-extending ninth time that the UK has hosted the contest, having last done so in Birmingham in 1998.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Liverpool has more galleries and national museums than any other city in the United Kingdom apart from London.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] National Museums Liverpool is the only English national collection based wholly outside London.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The Tate Liverpool gallery houses the modern art collection of the Tate in the North of England and was, until the opening of Tate Modern, the largest exhibition space dedicated to modern art in the United Kingdom.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The FACT centre hosts touring multimedia exhibitions, while the Walker Art Gallery houses one of the most impressive permanent collections of Pre-Raphaelite art in the world.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Sudley House contains another major collection of pre-20th-century art.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Liverpool University's Victoria Building was re-opened as a public art gallery and museum to display the university's artwork and historical collections which include the largest display of art by Audubon outside the US.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] A number of artists have also come from the city, including painter George Stubbs who was born in Liverpool in 1724.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The Liverpool Biennial festival of arts runs from mid-September to late November and comprises three main sections; the International, The Independents and New Contemporaries although fringe events are timed to coincide.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] It was during the 2004 festival that Yoko Ono's work "My mummy was beautiful" invited controversy when photographs of a woman's breast and crotch were exhibited on the main shopping street.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Felicia Hemans (née Browne) was born in Dale Street, Liverpool, in 1793, although she later moved to Flintshire, in Wales.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Felicia was born in Liverpool, a granddaughter of the Venetian consul in that city.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Her father's business soon brought the family to Denbighshire in North Wales, where she spent her youth.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] They made their home near Abergele and St.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Asaph (Flintshire), and it is clear that she came to regard herself as Welsh by adoption, later referring to Wales as "Land of my childhood, my home and my dead".
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Her first poems, dedicated to the Prince of Wales, were published in Liverpool in 1808, when she was only fourteen, arousing the interest of Percy Bysshe Shelley, who briefly corresponded with her.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] An engraving of a painting of The Wishing Gate. by S.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] It stood on the North Shore before the docks were built and was a place where farewells could be waved to departing voyagers.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] A number of notable authors have visited Liverpool, including Daniel Defoe, Washington Irving, Charles Dickens, Thomas De Quincey, Herman Melville, Nathaniel Hawthorne, Gerard Manley Hopkins and Hugh Walpole.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Defoe, after visiting the city, described it, as "one of the wonders of Britain in his 'Tour through England and Wales'".
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Melville's novel *Redburn* deals with the first seagoing voyage of 19 years old Wellingborough Redburn between New York and Liverpool in 1839.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Largely autobiographical, the middle sections of the book are set in Liverpool and describe the young merchantman's wanderings, and his reflections.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] From 1842 to 1869, Dickens visited the city to give public readings of his novels.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Hawthorne was stationed in Liverpool as United States consul between 1853 and 1856.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Hopkins served as priest at St Francis Xavier Church, Langdale St., Liverpool, between 1879 and 81.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Although he is not known to have ever visited Liverpool, Jung famously had a vivid dream of the city which he analysed in one of his works.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The writer, docker and political activist George Garrett was born in Seacombe, on the Wirral Peninsula in 1896 and was brought up in Liverpool's South end, around Park Road, the son of a fierce Liverpool–Irish Catholic mother and a staunch 'Orange' stevedore father.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] In the 1920s and 1930s, his organisation within the Seamen's Vigilance Committees, unemployed demonstrations, and hunger marches from Liverpool became part of a wider cultural force.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] He spoke at reconciliation meetings in sectarian Liverpool, and helped found the Unity Theatre in the 1930s as part of the Popular Front against the rise of fascism, particularly its echoes in the Spanish Civil War.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The novelist and playwright James Hanley (1897–1985) was born in Kirkdale, Liverpool, in 1897 (not Dublin, nor 1901 as he generally implied) to a working-class family.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Hanley grew up close to the docks and much of his early writing is about seamen.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] *The Furys* (1935) is first in a sequence of five loosely autobiographical novels about working-class life in Liverpool.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] James Hanley's brother, novelist Gerald Hanley (1916–92) was also born in Liverpool (not County Cork, Ireland, as he claimed).
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] While he published a number of novels he also wrote radio plays for the BBC as well as some film scripts, most notably *The Blue Max* (1966).
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] He was also one of several scriptwriters for a life of Gandhi (1964).
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Novelist Beryl Bainbridge (1932–2010) was born in Liverpool and raised in nearby Formby.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] She was primarily known for her works of psychological fiction, often set among the English working classes.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Bainbridge won the Whitbread Awards prize for best novel in 1977 and 1996 and was nominated five times for the Booker Prize.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] *The Times* newspaper named Bainbridge among their list of "The 50 greatest British writers since 1945".
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Farrell was born in Liverpool in 1935 but left at the outbreak of war in 1939.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] A novelist of Irish descent, Farrell gained prominence for his historical fiction, most notably his *Empire Trilogy* (*Troubles*, *The Siege of Krishnapur* and *The Singapore Grip*), dealing with the political and human consequences of British colonial rule.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] However, his career ended when he drowned in Ireland in 1979 at the age of 44.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Helen Forrester was the pen name of June Bhatia (née Huband) (1919–2011), who was known for her books about her early childhood in Liverpool during the Great Depression, including *Twopence to Cross the Mersey* (1974), as well as several works of fiction.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] During the late 1960s the city became well known for the Liverpool poets, who include Roger McGough and the late Adrian Henri.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] An anthology of poems, *The Mersey Sound*, written by Henri, McGough and Brian Patten, has sold well since it was first being published in 1967.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Liverpool has produced several noted writers of horror fiction, often set on Merseyside—Ramsey Campbell, Clive Barker and Peter Atkins among them.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] A collection of Liverpudlian horror fiction, *Spook City* was edited by a Liverpool expatriate, Angus Mackenzie, and introduced by Doug Bradley, also from Liverpool.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Bradley is famed for portraying Barker's creation Pinhead in the *Hellraiser* series of films.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Actors and actresses from elsewhere in the world have strong ties to the city, such as Canadian actor Mike Myers (whose parents were both from Liverpool) and American actress Halle Berry (whose mother was from Liverpool).
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Liverpool has a thriving and varied nightlife.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The majority of the city's late-night restaurants, bars, pubs, nightclubs, music venues and comedy clubs are located in a number of distinct districts.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] In 2023, figures from global data company Square show that night-time spending in bars and restaurants in Liverpool city centre outperformed all major UK cities, including London.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Figures by the Liverpool BID Company suggest that the busiest nights of the week in Liverpool city centre are Friday and Saturday.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Using cameras to track the flow of people in key locations between 7 pm and 4 am, at least 1.5 million people pass through the city centre every Friday night and almost 2 million people on Saturday nights.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The data demonstrates that Monday night is the quietest night of the week in the city centre and footfall then increases every single night to reach its peak on Saturday nights.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] 125,889 people worked in the city's night time economy as of 2022, according to the Liverpool BID Company.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Liverpool's nightlife is concentrated in a number of districts including Ropewalks which comprises Concert Square, St.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Peter's Square and the adjoining Seel Street and Duke Street.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Other popular areas include Hardman Street, the Cavern Quarter, Baltic Triangle, Royal Albert Dock and the city's Pride Quarter, which is home to a large number of LGBT venues.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] In the city's suburbs, Lark Lane in Aigburth is noted for an abundance of bars and late-night venues.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] In Liverpool primary and secondary education is available in various forms supported by the state including secular, Church of England, Jewish, and Roman Catholic.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Islamic education is available at primary level, but there is no secondary provision.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] One of Liverpool's important early schools was The Liverpool Blue Coat School; founded in 1708 as a charitable school.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The Liverpool Blue Coat School is the top-performing school in the city with 100% 5 or more A*-C grades at GCSE resulting in the 30th best GCSE results in the country and an average point score per student of 1087.4 in A/AS levels.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Other notable schools include Liverpool College founded in 1840 Merchant Taylors' School founded in 1620.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Another of Liverpool's notable senior schools is St.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Edward's College situated in the West Derby area of the city.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Historic grammar schools, such as the Liverpool Institute High School and Liverpool Collegiate School—both closed in the 1980s—are still remembered as centres of academic excellence.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Bellerive Catholic College is the city's top-performing non-selective school, based upon GCSE results in 2007.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Liverpool has three universities: the University of Liverpool, Liverpool John Moores University and Liverpool Hope University.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Edge Hill University, founded as a teacher-training college in the Edge Hill district of Liverpool, is now located in Ormskirk in South-West Lancashire.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Liverpool is also home to the Liverpool Institute for Performing Arts (LIPA).
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The University of Liverpool was established in 1881 as University College Liverpool.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] In 1884, it became part of the federal Victoria University.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Following a Royal Charter and Act of Parliament in 1903, it became an independent university, the University of Liverpool, with the right to confer its own degrees.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] It was the first university to offer degrees in biochemistry, architecture, civic design, veterinary science, oceanography and social science.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Liverpool Hope University, which was formed through the merger of three colleges, the earliest of which was founded in 1844, gained university status in 2005.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] It is the only ecumenical university in Europe.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] It is situated on both sides of Taggart Avenue in Childwall and has a second campus in the city centre (the Cornerstone).
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The Liverpool School of Tropical Medicine, founded to address some of the problems created by trade, continues today as a post-graduate school affiliated with the University of Liverpool and houses an anti-venom repository.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Liverpool John Moores University was previously a polytechnic, and gained status in 1992.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] It is named in honour of Sir John Moores, one of the founders of the Littlewoods football pools and retail group, who was a major benefactor.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The institution was previously owned and run by Liverpool City Council.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] It traces it lineage to the Liverpool Mechanics' institute, opened in 1823, making it by this measure England's third-oldest university.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The city has one further education college, City of Liverpool College in the city centre.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Liverpool City Council operates Burton Manor, a residential adult education college in nearby Burton, on the Wirral Peninsula.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] There are two Jewish schools in Liverpool, both belonging to the King David Foundation.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] King David School, Liverpool, is the High School and the King David Primary School.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] There is also a King David Kindergarten, featured in the community centre of Harold House.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] These schools are all run by the King David Foundation located in Harold House in Childwall; conveniently next door to the Childwall Synagogue.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Liverpool is one of the most successful footballing cities in England, and is home to two top flight Premier League teams.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Everton F.C. was founded in 1878 and was one of the twelve founder members of the Football League.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Liverpool F.C. were founded in 1892 and play at Anfield.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Between them, the clubs have won 28 English First Division titles, 12 FA Cup titles, 10 League Cup titles, 6 European Cup titles, 1 FIFA Club World Cup title, 1 European Cup Winners' Cup title, 3 UEFA Cup titles, and 24 FA Charity Shields.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The two clubs contest the Merseyside derby, dubbed the 'friendly derby'.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Despite the name the fixture is known for its keen rivalry, having seen more sending-offs in this fixture than any other.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Unlike many other derbies it is not rare for families in the city to contain supporters of both clubs.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Liverpool F.C. is the English and British club with the most European Cup titles with six, the latest in 2019.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Liverpool has played at Anfield since 1892, when the club was formed to occupy the stadium following Everton's departure due to a dispute with their landlord.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Liverpool are still playing there 125 years later, although the ground has been completely rebuilt since the 1970s.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The Spion Kop (rebuilt as an all-seater stand in 1994–95) was the most famous part of the ground, gaining cult status across the world due to the songs and celebrations of the many fans who packed onto its terraces.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Anfield as capacity for 54,000 spectators in comfort and is a distinctive landmark in an area filled with smaller and older buildings.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Liverpool club also has a multimillion-pound youth training facility called The Academy.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] After leaving Anfield in 1892, Everton moved to Goodison Park on the opposite side of Stanley Park.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The ground was opened on 24 August 1892, by Lord Kinnaird and Frederick Wall of the FA but the first crowds to attend the ground saw a short athletics meeting followed by a selection of music and a fireworks display.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Everton's first game there was on 2 September 1892 when they beat Bolton 4–2.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] It was one of the host venues during the 1966 FIFA World Cup.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] It now has the capacity for just under 40,000 spectators all-seated, but the last expansion took place in 1994 when a new Park End Stand gave the stadium an all-seater capacity.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The Goodison Road Stand dates back to the 1970s, while the Gwladys Street Stand and Bullens Road Stand are refurbished pre-Second World War structures.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Everton has recently completed the process of relocating, with a stadium move first mooted as early as 1996.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The club relocated to the multimillion-pound Everton Stadium designed by the American architect Dan Meis at the nearby Bramley-Moore Dock on the River Mersey waterfront for the beginning of the 2025/26 season, with ground broken on the project in August 2021.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The new stadium will have a capacity of 52,888 which could be expanded to 62,000 demand permitting and it will be a host venue for the UEFA Euro 2028.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Everton also have a multimillion-pound training facility based at Finch Farm.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The Everton Women's Team play in the Women's Super League and moved into Goodison Park following the men's team's exit, having previously played at Walton Hall Park Stadium.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Despite being a popular sport in Northern England, professional rugby league failed to develop in the Liverpool city region.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Liverpool City was the city's first professional club, but only competed in the 1906–07 season where they finished 26th of 26.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Despite the failure to establish a team, the Northern Union scheduled four Kangaroo Tour matches at Goodison Park in their first three tours to Great Britain between 1908 and 1922, hosting three English League XIII games and one Lancashire game.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Professional rugby league did not return to the city until 1934 with the formation of Liverpool Stanley.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The following year, England played Wales at the club's ground in the 1935 European Rugby League Championship.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Stanley competed until 1968 twice reaching the playoffs.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The club hosted Australia in their 1956–57 tour, the first time the Kangaroos had played in Liverpool since 1922.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Professional rugby league was again absent from the city until Anfield hosted the 1989 Charity Shield where Widnes beat Wigan 27–22.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Two years later, the stadium hosted the 1991 World Club Challenge where Wigan beat Penrith 21–4.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Trying to capitalise on the growing interest in the sport, not just in Liverpool but across the country, St Helens (the only professional club in the wider Merseyside region) held a number of home games at Anfield in the mid to late 1990s.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] However wider problems with the sport as a result of the Super League war stopped this initiative.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The professional game would again be absent from city until the mid and late 2010s when Anfield again hosted the 2016 Rugby League Four Nations final, Test 2 of the 2018 Baskerville Shield, and Magic Weekend in 2019.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Everton's new Bramley-Moore Dock Stadium will host Test 2 of the 2025 Ashes.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Boxing is massively popular in Liverpool.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The city has a proud heritage and history in the sport and is home to around 22 amateur boxing clubs, which are responsible for producing many successful boxers, such as Nel Tarleton, Alan Rudkin, John Conteh, Andy Holligan, Liam Smith, Paul Hodkinson, Tony Bellew and Robin Ried.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Boxing events are usually hosted at the Echo Arena and Liverpool Olympia within the city, although the former home of Liverpool boxing was the renowned Liverpool Stadium.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Aintree Racecourse in the adjacent Metropolitan Borough of Sefton is home to the world's most famous steeple-chase, the Randox Grand National which takes place annually in early April.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The race meeting attracts horse owners/ jockeys from around the world to compete in the demanding 4-mile (6.5-kilometre) and 30-fence course.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] There have been many memorable moments of the Grand National, for instance, the 100/1 outsider Foinavon in 1967, the dominant Red Rum and Ginger McCain of the 1970s and Mon Mome (100/1) who won the 2009 meeting.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] In 2010, the National became the first horse race to be televised in high-definition in the UK.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The Royal Liverpool Golf Club, situated in the nearby town of Hoylake on the Wirral Peninsula, has hosted The Open Championship on a number of occasions, most recently in 2023.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Liverpool once contained four greyhound tracks, Seaforth Greyhound Stadium (1933–1965), Breck Park Stadium (1927–1948), Stanley Greyhound Stadium (1927–1961) and White City Stadium (1932–1973).
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Breck Park also hosted boxing bouts and both Stanley and Seaforth hosted Motorcycle speedway.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] In August 2012, Liverpool gymnast Beth Tweddle won an Olympic bronze medal in London 2012 in the uneven bars at her third Olympic Games, thus becoming the most decorated British gymnast in history.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Park Road Gymnastics Centre provides training to a high level.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Liverpool has produced several swimmers who have represented their nation at major championships such as the Olympic Games.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The most notable of which is Steve Parry who claimed a bronze medal at the 2004 Athens Olympics in the 200m butterfly.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Others include Herbert Nickel Haresnape, Margaret Kelly, Shellagh Ratcliffe and Austin Rawlinson.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] There is a purpose-built aquatics centre at Wavertree Sports Park, which opened in 2008.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The City of Liverpool Swimming Club has been National Speedo League Champions 8 out of the last 11 years.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The city is the hub of the Liverpool and District Cricket Competition, an ECB Premier League.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Sefton Park and Liverpool are the league's founder members based in the city with Wavertree, Alder and Old Xaverians clubs having joined the league more recently.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Liverpool plays host Lancashire County Cricket Club as an outground most seasons, including six of eight home County Championship games during Lancashire's 2011 title winning campaign while Old Trafford was refurbished.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Since 2014 Liverpool Cricket Club has played host to the annual Tradition-ICAP Liverpool International tennis tournament, which has seen tennis stars such as Novak Djokovic, David Ferrer, Mardy Fish, Laura Robson and Caroline Wozniacki.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Previously this had been held at Calderstones Park, situated in Allerton in the south of the city.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Liverpool Tennis Development Programme at Wavertree Tennis Centre is one of the largest in the UK.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Professional basketball came to the city in 2007 with the entry of Everton Tigers, later known as Mersey Tigers, into the elite British Basketball League.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The club was originally associated with Everton F.C., and was part of the *Toxteth Tigers* youth development programme, which reached over 1,500 young people every year.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The Tigers began to play in Britain's top league for the 2007–08 season, playing at the Greenbank Sports Academy before moving into the newly completed Echo Arena during that season.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] After the 2009–10 season, Everton F.C. withdrew funding from the Tigers, who then changed their name to Mersey Tigers.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The club were expelled from the British Basketball League in 2013 due to financial problems.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Liverpool is one of three cities which still host the traditional sport of British baseball and it hosts the annual England-Wales international match every two years, alternating with Cardiff and Newport.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Liverpool Trojans are the oldest existing baseball club in the UK.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The 2014 Tour of Britain cycle race began in Liverpool on 7 September, using a city centre circuit to complete 130 km (80.8 mi) of racing.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The Tour of Britain took nine stages and finished in London on 14 September.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] A 2016 study of UK fitness centres found that, of the top 20 UK urban areas, Liverpool had the highest number of leisure and sports centres per capita, with 4.3 centres per 100,000 of the city population.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The city has one daily newspaper: the *Echo*, published by Reach plc.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] *The Liverpool Daily Post* was also published until 2013.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The UK's first online-only weekly newspaper called *Southport Reporter* (*Southport and Mersey Reporter*), is also one of the many other news outlets that cover the city.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The independent media organisation *The Post* also covers Liverpool, while *Nerve* magazine publishes articles and reviews of cultural events.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Liverpool TV is a local television station serving Liverpool City Region and surrounding areas.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The station is owned and operated by Made Television Ltd and forms part of a group of eight local TV stations.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] It broadcasts from studios and offices in Liverpool.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The ITV region which covers Liverpool is ITV Granada.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] In 2006, the Television company opened a new newsroom in the Royal Liver Building.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Granada's regional news broadcasts were produced at the Royal Albert Dock News Centre during the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The BBC also opened a new newsroom on Hanover Street in 2006.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] ITV's daily magazine programme *This Morning* was broadcast from studios at Royal Albert Dock until 1996, when production was moved to London.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Granada's short-lived shopping channel "Shop!" was also produced in Liverpool until it was cancelled in 2002.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Liverpool is the home of the TV production company Lime Pictures, formerly Mersey Television, which produced the now-defunct soap operas *Brookside* and *Grange Hill*.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] It also produces the soap opera *Hollyoaks*, which was formerly filmed in Chester and began on Channel 4 in 1995.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] All three series were/are largely filmed in the Childwall area of Liverpool.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Radio stations include BBC Radio Merseyside, Hits Radio Liverpool, Greatest Hits Radio, Capital Liverpool, In Demand Radio and Liverpool Live Radio.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Liverpool has also featured in films; see List of films set in Liverpool for some of them.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] In films the city has "doubled" for London, Paris, New York, Chicago, Moscow, Dublin, Venice and Berlin.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The first overseas consulate of the United States was opened in Liverpool in 1790, and it remained operational for almost two centuries.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Today, a large number of consulates are located in the city serving Chile, Denmark, Estonia, Finland, France, Germany, Hungary, Iceland, Italy, Netherlands, Norway, Romania, Sweden and Thailand.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] Tunisian & Ivory Coast Consulates are located in the neighbouring Metropolitan Borough of Sefton.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/liverpool-p03] The following people and military units have received the Freedom of the City of Liverpool.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] The county is highly urbanised, with an area of 249 square miles (645 km2) and a population of 1,475,541 in 2024.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] Liverpool is in the centre of the county on the east bank of the Mersey Estuary, and Birkenhead opposite on the west bank.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] St Helens is in the east of the county, and Southport in the north.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] For local government purposes the county comprises five metropolitan boroughs: Knowsley, St Helens, Sefton, Wirral, and Liverpool.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] The borough councils, together with that of Halton in Cheshire, collaborate through the Liverpool City Region Combined Authority.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] What is now Merseyside was a largely rural area until the Industrial Revolution, when Liverpool and Birkenhead's positions on the Mersey Estuary enabled them to expand.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] Liverpool became a major port, heavily involved in the Atlantic slave trade and in supplying cotton to the mills of Lancashire, and Birkenhead developed into a centre for shipbuilding.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] Innovations during this period included the first inter-city railway, the first publicly-funded civic park, advances in dock technology, and a pioneering elevated electrical railway.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] The county was established in 1974, before which the entirety of the Wirral was in Cheshire and the remainder of the county was in Lancashire.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] Merseyside is notable for its sport, music, and cultural institutions.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] The Merseybeat genre developed in what is now the county, which has also produced many artists and bands, including the Beatles.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] The county contains several football clubs, with Everton and Liverpool playing in the Premier League.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] The Royal Liverpool and Royal Birkdale golf clubs have hosted The Open Championship 22 times between them, and the Grand National is the most valuable jump race in Europe.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] National Museums Liverpool comprises nine museums and art galleries.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] According to the OED, the earliest use of the word Merseyside (presumably as a general term for the lands surrounding the river) is from 1899.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] The county of Merseyside was created in 1974 from areas previously part of the administrative counties of Lancashire and Cheshire, along with the county boroughs of Birkenhead, Bootle, Liverpool, St Helens, Southport, and Wallasey.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] Merseyside had been designated a "Special Review" area in the Local Government Act 1958.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] The Local Government Commission for England started a review of this area in 1962, based around the core county boroughs of Liverpool, Bootle, Birkenhead and Wallasey.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] Further areas, including Widnes and Runcorn, were added to the Special Review Area by Order in 1965.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] Draft proposals were published in 1965, but the commission never completed its final proposals as it was abolished in 1966.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] This would have included four districts: Southport/Crosby, Liverpool/Bootle, St Helens/Widnes and Wirral/Chester.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] Meanwhile, in 1970 the Merseyside Passenger Transport Executive (which operates today under the *Merseytravel* brand) was set up, covering Liverpool, Sefton, Wirral and Knowsley, but excluding Southport and St Helens.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] The Redcliffe-Maud Report was rejected by the Conservative government elected in 1970, but the concept of a two-tier metropolitan area based on the Mersey area was retained in a white paper published in 1971.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] The Local Government Bill presented to Parliament involved a substantial trimming from the white paper, excluding the northern and southern fringes of the area, Chester, and Ellesmere Port; and, for the first time, including Southport, whose council had requested to be included.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] Further alterations took place in Parliament, with Skelmersdale being removed from the area, and a proposed district including St Helens and Huyton being subdivided into what are now the metropolitan boroughs of St Helens and Knowsley.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] Merseyside was established as a metropolitan county on 1 April 1974 under the Local Government Act 1972, as part of a major reform of local government in England and Wales.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] Following the creation of Merseyside, Merseytravel expanded to take in St Helens and Southport.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] At first, the county had a two-tier system of local government: the five metropolitan boroughs shared power with the Merseyside County Council, which was based in Liverpool.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] The first elections of the 99 members of the county council were held in April 1973, in advance of the formal establishment of the council on 1 April 1974.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] The body had a strategic role in areas such as transport; the boroughs had more powers than non-metropolitan districts, in that they were additionally responsible for education and social services, responsibilities allocated to county councils elsewhere.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] In 1986 the county council, along with all other metropolitan county councils, was abolished under the Local Government Act 1985.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] Thus the boroughs are now effectively unitary authorities.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] Merseyside is divided into two parts by the Mersey estuary; the Wirral is on the west side of the estuary, upon the Wirral Peninsula, and the rest of the county lies on the east side.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] The eastern part of Merseyside borders onto Lancashire to the north and Greater Manchester to the east, with both parts of the county bordering Cheshire to the south.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] The territory comprising the county of Merseyside previously formed part of the administrative counties of Lancashire (east of the River Mersey) and Cheshire (west of the River Mersey).
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] The two parts are linked by the two Mersey Tunnels, the Wirral line of Merseyrail, and the Mersey Ferry.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] Merseyside contains green belt interspersed throughout the county, surrounding the Liverpool urban area, as well as across the Mersey in the Wirral area, with further pockets extending towards and surrounding Southport, as part of the western edge of the North West Green Belt.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] All the county's districts contain some portion of belt.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] Merseyside comprises the metropolitan boroughs of Liverpool, Knowsley, Sefton, St Helens and Wirral.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] The combined authority is led by the Mayor of the Liverpool City Region, Steve Rotheram, who was elected in 2017 and re-elected in 2021 and in 2024.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] The planning and commissioning of care within Merseyside is the responsibility of an integrated care system, NHS Cheshire and Merseyside, which covers NHS and other care services within the Cheshire and Merseyside areas.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] It also oversees Cheshire and Merseyside Health and Care Partnership.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] NHS Cheshire and Merseyside serves a combined population of 2.7 million as of 2024.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] Merseyside is served by six motorways: the M58 to the north, M56 to the south, M6 & M62 to the east and M53 to the west.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] The M57 acts as an outer ring road and bypass for the city of Liverpool itself.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] The River Mersey is crossed by Queensway Tunnel and Kingsway Tunnel, which link Liverpool to Birkenhead and Wallasey respectively, and by the Silver Jubilee Bridge and Mersey Gateway Bridge, which link Runcorn and Widnes.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] The Mersey Gateway Bridge opened in 2017 and is designed to improve transport links between Widnes and Runcorn and other key locations in the vicinity.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] National Cycle Route 56 and National Cycle Route 62 pass through the region, the former along the Wirral and the latter from Southport to Runcorn.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] Major bus companies are Stagecoach Merseyside and Arriva North West.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] Liverpool One bus station serves as a terminus for national coach travel.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] Liverpool Lime Street main line station is Merseyside's primary inter-city railway station, being used by 10.46 million passengers in 2021–22.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] Services are provided by Avanti West Coast, East Midlands Railway, London Northwestern Railway, Northern Trains, TransPennine Express and Transport for Wales; between them, they serve destinations across the UK.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] Merseyrail is the county's urban rail system and is operated by Merseytravel, the combined passenger transport executive for the Liverpool City Region.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] The network has 66 stations on two lines; the Northern Line covers the centre of the county and the Wirral Line covers the eponymous peninsula.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] The two lines meet in Liverpool City Centre and Liverpool Central is the county's most-used station, with 10.75 million passengers in 2021–22.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] The network extends to Ormskirk in Lancashire, and Ellesmere Port and Chester in Cheshire.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] Merseytravel brands the network in the east of the county as the *City Line*, but the services on it are not operated by Merseyrail.
[src:claire-house-children-s-hospice/merseyside] The Borderlands line connects the west of the Wirral to Wales and is operated by Transport for Wales.
